bnn: Cai-Ing-Un contong daihio siho taho to moliva siho malka Incomin
english: President Tsai Ing-wen's Apology to the Indigenous Peoples on Behalf of the Government.

bnn: Isia maposanhan-dosa painsanan tanangaos to aip to hanian, imita sinosan to kimpo, maza ‹ sanpao › hai paciloshoan to ‹ Incomin ›. Sain to sinpacilosho hai, mapin-okain maisna habas to sinsatamal, mapithasin taho to kata Incomin sidoh hai, nao to taini Taioantan. Kanasaicin, aip to hanian, nakaslod kata modan. Nadaihio saikin seho, masina sia Incomin sidoh, maisna isang topa to moliva sasaipok. Pat saba painsanancin, kamo hai malmimihdi mosaso kahaingion, daihio saikin sasaipok topa to: Totoza seho to moliva sinmalka mo.
english: On this day 22 years ago, the term "shanbao" (mountain people) in the Additional Articles of our Constitution was replaced with the proper name: "indigenous people." This correction not only did away with a discriminatory term, but also highlighted the status of indigenous peoples as Taiwan's "original owners." From this basis, today, we are taking another step forward. To all indigenous peoples of Taiwan: On behalf of the government, I express to you our deepest apology. For the four centuries of pain and mistreatment you have endured, I apologize to you on behalf of the government.

bnn: Latoza saikin to, sao aip to hanian, oskonanta mihomis mandidingalan to bonon hai, aizang bonon iniliskinan maingo to okas moliva. Cissaicin, aip to hanian asa saikin to daihio seho topang to moliva sinsaipok. Taisbananin to painlivan hai samaszangan mas nao to namaopacia, anis doma sidoh to inihdian hai, makas-ang to nao to nalahaip saicin. Cissaicin, matodoldol saikin aip to hanian saincin, naasa kangaos kahna mapaokbas iniliskinan.
english: I know that even now, there are some around us who see no need to apologize. But that is the most important reason why I am representing the government to issue this apology today. To see what was unfair in the past as a matter of course, or to treat the pain of other ethnic peoples as an unavoidable part of human development, this is the first mindset that we, standing here today, resolve to change and overturn.

bnn: Naansansan saikin taho to, mavia to nataho Incomin to moliva. Taioan to dalahcin, pat saba painsanan to tanangaos hai, nao to aizain katsaincin bonon. Manano hai salin-anak mapasaipok, aizan an-anak to halinga, bongka, samo, katdan to dalah. Moso, ni naia cinopa to mahto, haito aiza doma sidoh taosaincin.
english: Let me put in simple terms why we are apologizing to the indigenous peoples. Four hundred years ago, there were already people living in Taiwan. These first inhabitants lived their lives and had their own languages, cultures, customs, and domains. But then, without their consent, another group of people arrived on these shores, and in the course of history, took everything from the first inhabitants who, on the land they have known most intimately, became displaced, foreign, non-mainstream, and marginalized.

bnn: Taisbananin to inihomisan hai maopacin to, aipincin laidazo to bonon, mahalav naia mas nao to takisancin to bonon. Kazin naia posbaion sia inihomisan to asang, min-oni movasvas to bonon, min-oni niin pasiamon, kazin sahalmangan. Tasa sidoh to maidaza, haipa ni to piniskadazaon sia doma sidoh to inihdian. Mais ni kata cinopa to mamantok mapiszang imita kokka, namahtobin kata sahalmang saicin, asa mamantok to istopa. At mastan kahosbon hai, asa seho to mosohis mamantok miliskin, cissaicin saikin aip to hanian matodoldol saincin.
english: The success of one ethnic people can be built on the suffering of another. Unless we deny that we are a country of justice, we must face up to this history. We must tell the truth. And then, most importantly, the government must genuinely reflect on this past. This is why I stand here today.

bnn: Aiza tasa ahil topaon to "Taioan tongso." Isia sintongaos to halinga hai topa to: "Ukan Taioan mas paitasan. Inkasia Holanda kitngab, Conconkon sidoh kozakoza, mailngaos Lipon to seho saipok." Maopacia ito Pot palihabasan. Haito maza Incomin sidoh hai nao to maisna habas katsaincin, matmoza bongka mas taiklas, ispasosono maikingna. Haito kaz kata kanasia kain-asang sidoh to saidoan mapatas lainihaiban. Cismaopacia, daihio saikin mas seho masiaopa sia Incomin sidoh topa to moliva seho malka bonon.
english: There is a book called "The General History of Taiwan" published in 1920. In its foreword are these words: "Taiwan had no history. The Dutch pioneered it, the Koxinga Kingdom built it, and the Qing Empire managed it." This is a typical Han view of history. The truth is that indigenous peoples have been here for thousands of years, with rich culture and wisdom that have been passed down through generations. But we only know to write history from the perspective of the dominant. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

bnn: Holanda mas Consonkong hai maipalatpo mapataz at maihalav mas Tangavolan sidoh, masa mailngangaos Liponto to seho hai, pailkapataz abdit, masa sin Lipon saipok hai, kaspokanin sana naicia saipok, masa pailkanahtongin pasampanah hai sin Taolotan saipok hai, mavaiviin sinsaipok Incomin sidoh. Isia pat saba to painsanan, kain-asang, mahalav dalah, mahalav Incomis to kinli. Cismaopacia, daihio saikin seho masinasia Incomin sidoh topa to moliva sain.
english: The Dutch and the Koxinga Kingdom massacred and exploited the Pingpu ethnic group. The Qing Empire presided over bloody confrontations and suppression. Colonial Japan put in place comprehensive savage policies. And the post- war ROC government undertook assimilation policies. For 400 years, every regime that has come to Taiwan has brutally violated the rights of indigenous peoples through armed invasion and land seizure. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

bnn: Kanasia Incomin sidoh sia maisnahabas to dailaz saipok asang malka-minihomis. Haito, isia namapinsial kokkacin, nin Incomin sidoh mahto salin-anak. Montonohin maisnakitngab to dailaz, itoskon to iniliskinan hai, nin amin saaopancia. Cismaopacia, daihio saikin mas seho masiaopa sia Incomin sidoh topa to moliva seho malka bonon.
english: Indigenous peoples maintain tribal order according to traditional customs, and ecological balance according to traditional wisdom. But in the process of modern state-building, indigenous peoples lost the right to steer their own course and govern their own affairs. The fabric of traditional societies was torn apart, and the collective rights of peoples were not recognized. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

bnn: Naoto aizan Incomin sidoh mas halinga, maisna isnavan min Lipon to sinnava, isia 1945 painsanan kitngab, lahnot seho malas-bonon, at maszang monghano ito Incomin sidoh haling. Sopahin Tangavolan sidoh niin haiap malas-ananak to halinga palinoto. Maisna habas to seho, ni to masanbot mapalmamaopa Incomis sidoh maisna kitngab to bongka. Cismaopacia, daihio saikin mas seho masiaopa sia Incomin sidoh topa to moliva seho malka bonon.
english: Indigenous peoples had their own languages. However, with Japanese rule aiming to assimilate and turn all into imperial subjects, and with the ROC government banning tribal languages after 1945, indigenous peoples' languages suffered great losses. Most Pingpu languages have disappeared. Successive governments have been negligent in the protection of indigenous cultures. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

bnn: Todip to painsanan, seho hai makotodi niang Pangkalkalan sidoh haiaphaiap hai vailan mas dingki-taki. Takisia Lan-i bonon to lotbo hai bason mas dingki-taki. Cismaopacia, daihio saikin mas seho masiaopa sia Pangkalkalan sidoh topa to moliva seho malka mo.
english: Without the knowledge of the Yami tribe, the government stored nuclear waste on Orchid Island. Tribe members on the island had to suffer the negative consequences. For this, I apologize to the Yami people on behalf of the government.

bnn: Vaivi sidoh kaosia Taioancin, takisia ohaivas vali to Tangavolan hai, lanadan mas iahdi. Maza lasasais kan-asang hai mapis-oka inaicia to sidoh. Cismaopacia, daihio saikin mas seho masiaopa sia Tangavolan topa to moliva seho malka mo.
english: Ever since outsiders began arriving in Taiwan, the Pingpu ethnic group on the western plains have born the brunt of the impact. One ruling power after another eroded the individual and collective identities of the Pingpu ethnic group. For this, I apologize to the Pingpu ethnic group on behalf of the government.

bnn: Masa min-onin minsio kokka, taiaza mas Incomin sidoh ondo to sintotopa. Seho hai aintalam malmanano to napin-sialon. Aizan kata mas "Incomin sidoh to kanadan," haito ni seho kapimaopa kozakoza sahosbo samashing saicin. Malaitaz kaimin, ni to macitpong, ni to mapal-amin. Cismaopacia, daihio saikin mas seho masiaopa sia Incomin topa to moliva seho malka bonon.
english: After the democratic transition, the country began to respond to the appeals of indigenous movements. The government made certain promises and efforts. Today, we have an Indigenous Peoples Basic Law that is quite advanced. However, government agencies have not given sufficient weight to this law. Our actions have not been fast enough, comprehensive enough or sound enough. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

bnn: Topaon Taioan to "maisopah bongka" to katdan. Haito, saolaopako, Incomin sidoh to kaihatban, ispasnava, kaisoian, iapavcin to isasaipok, mapasidahdah mas ni to Incomin. Mosaso, maldaok to samakong sakolaz Incomin sidoh. Kaoman seho kinozkozan, oka doma sidoh minaopa mas Incomin sidoh to lainihaiban, inihdian sinmas tailpatazan. Cismaopacia, daihio saikin mas seho masiaopa sia Incomin sidoh topa to moliva seho malka bonon.
english: Taiwan is known as a culturally diverse society. But even today, indicators on health, education, economic livelihood, political participation and more still show gaps between indigenous and non- indigenous peoples. Meanwhile, stereotypes and even discrimination against indigenous peoples have not gone away. The government has not done enough, so indigenous peoples have suffered pain and frustration unknown to other ethnic peoples. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

bnn: Kaoman inam kinozkozan, maisna habas ni kaimin minhaiap at mailmanano, kazin kamo sao laopako maldaok to malmimihdi, tozatoza to moliva maopacia. Aip to hanian topa to moliva, anatopa to maaitin topa, haito sain hai kangab. Ni saikin makasang to maza ito Incomin sidoh sia pat saba painsanan to inihdian hai, nacis-oni tasa to paitasan, tosan topa to moliva at paladoazin mas painliavan. Haito maisna isang saikin mastatala natopa to moliva, aopa sain hai tasto-kokka to bonon mapaladoaz to kitngab.
english: Our efforts have fallen short, and succeeding generations have been blind to this inadequacy. Because of this, your hardship has continued to this day. For this we are truly sorry. Today's apology is long overdue, but it is a beginning. I do not expect any one speech or phrase of apology to wipe away four centuries of pain and suffering by the indigenous peoples. But I do hope with all my heart that today's apology will set this country and all its people on the path towards reconciliation.

bnn: Namakosia saikin Incomin sidoh to taiklas, mapishaiap aip to sinkozakoza. Taialo to haling, "mamantok" hai Balay. "patohavit" hai Sbalay, kaz Balay to tanangaos sosan mas S. Maza mamantok mas patohavit hai, maitasa to halingaz. Sintopa to, mamantok to patohavit, asa to maisna isang samantok to maimakoa dao at namahto minsia.
english: Please allow me to shed light on this occasion with a piece of indigenous wisdom. In the Atayal language, truth is called "Balay," and reconciliation is called "Sbalay," so you simply add an "S" sound to "Balay." Truth and reconciliation are in fact two related concepts. In other words, only by facing the truth sincerely can reconciliation be attained.

bnn: Isia Incomin sidoh to bongka, mais aiza bonon panliva malka doma to bonon, mais asa mapaladoaz, maza madadaingaz hai mas-anpok naicia. Ni to tosansan topa to moliva, asa naia to patopaon mas anak- anak to iniliskinan. Mais tonahtongin amin at mapasohisin haling hai, mapahod madadaingaz naicia mas davos, taisbanan to painlivan hai toza to paladoazin. Saicin topaon to Sbalay.
english: In indigenous cultures, when a tribe member has offended another and intends to reconcile, an elder brings together the offender and the offended - not to produce a direct apology, but to allow each side to frankly share their inner journeys. When this truth-telling concludes, the elder calls for everyone to drink together, so that what is past is truly past. This is "Sbalay."

bnn: Mashadang saikin aip to hanian, maza seho mas Incomin sidoh to Sbalay. Ni saikin maming mas taisbanan to painlivan, sinmas maimakoa. Natopa amin sanganin Incomin sidoh mas iniliskinan. Ni saikin topa to macinso a ladoaz. Haito, mahtoang kata mastala akitmatan, habas to painlivan hai naniin mohna, aiza to hanian, sain to kokka hai namamantok to maiaopa mapaladoaz.
english: I hope today's occasion can be a "Sbalay" between the government and the indigenous peoples. I have spoken of past mistakes and truths the best I can, with nothing held back. In a moment, our indigenous friends will speak. I do not dare ask you to forgive, here and now. But I sincerely ask you to sustain the hope that past wrongs will not be repeated, and that one day, this country can see true reconciliation.

bnn: Aip to hanian hai kangab, mapaladoaz to iskozakoza hai, ni to sia Incomin sidoh sinmas Tangavolan, siamas ito seho to nakozakozaon. Haiap saikin to mais kaz makongolos topa to moliva hai kaomanang. Maisna laopako ito seho sinmalko Incomin sidoh hai, nasaitan mahto kanadan mas kokkatan mapaladoaz.
english: Today is only a beginning. The duty for reconciliation lies not with the indigenous peoples and the Pingpu ethnic group, but with the government. I know that words of apology alone are not enough. What we actually do for the indigenous peoples will decide whether reconciliation succeeds or stumbles.

bnn: Isaincin saikin mapishaiap to, isia Contongho hai namapin-aiza "Incomin sidoh mantok to likisi mas mokbas mapiszang to iingkai." Makoonisaikinkokkatotanghapopaliskadanto ngan mas-anpok, moskon sidohsidoh sinihailaz to bonon Namapaloszang palihansiap kokka alngangasan to nakozakozaon.
english: Therefore, I am here to announce that we are setting up an Indigenous Historical Justice and Transitional Justice Commission under the Presidential Office. As the head of state, I will serve as convener and work hand in hand with tribal representatives to pursue historical justice. We will also discuss, on the basis of equality, the future policy direction of this country.

bnn: Mapihosbo saikin topa to, isia contongho to iingkai hai nakastanan sahosbo hai, kokka mas Incomin sidoh to mapaloszang. Sidohsidoh to sihailazon hai, nakanasia sidoh mas asang itoskon to sinpatopa. Sain hai ito sidoh itoskon to sinpalihansiap, mahto mapatopa maisna isang to iniliskinan.
english: I want to stress that this commission places the greatest importance on equality between the country and the indigenous peoples. The election of tribal representatives, including for the Pingpu ethnic group, will take as basis the consensus of peoples and tribes. This commission will serve as a mechanism for collective decision-making by indigenous peoples, and will ensure that the voices of tribe members find true expression.

bnn: Aizang, naiskalonanko sincongin to madailaza oanpokan to hanian palioni "Incomin sidoh kanadan to dailaz." Iingkai itoskon to sinpatopa, maza ima to Ing mapatopa to napikon mapinsia. Maszang mas masolot kilim taikihabasang, lainson Incomin sidoh to salin-anak, mapiszang is-ihomis, mas-ono pasnava sinmas mapantala bongka, mapihatba lotbo, sinmas saipok taosia bokzav to bonon.
english: In addition, I will request that our Executive Yuan convene regularly the Indigenous Peoples Basic Law Promotion Committee, and use the Yuan's authority to coordinate and handle matters related to any consensus reached by the above-mentioned commission. These matters include the following: to retrieve historical memories, to promote indigenous self-government, to seek fair economic development, to ensure continuation of culture and education, to safeguard indigenous health, and to protect the rights of urban indigenous peoples, etc.

bnn: Laopako ispakapimaopa to dailaz mas Incomin sidoh mailanhabas to bongka, aiza ni to patokdado, nasihaizaz kata mas mahansiap bongka to bonon masingadah "mindangaz Incomin sidoh malka ispakapimaopa dailaz," kabahlo mas nakanadan, mapis-oka Incomin sidoh to mailanhabas to dailaz sinmas palatongtong laopako kokka kanadan to dailaz.
english: Where modern laws and indigenous traditional cultures are at odds, we will set up an Indigenous Legal Service Center with a high degree of cultural sensitivity, to reduce through institutional design the growing clashes between indigenous customs and modern laws.

bnn: Naiskalonanko malkasia to macinsoa kozakoza, Incomin sidoh mais cis-oni mailanhabas to dalaz, isia kaitdadan to dalah, cisoni naikanakon ni to isbaliv at mapataz ni to mahto patazon to takilibos, at damon sisaisan iksobon. Namoskon kata palihansiap to napasikon mapoltav.
english: I will ask the relevant agencies to immediately pull together cases in which indigenous community members have been indicted or sentenced for hunting, where the hunting was done in accordance with traditional customs, on traditional lands, and for non-transactional needs, and where the animals hunted were not protected by conservation laws. For such cases we will deliberate solutions.

bnn: Natopaonko amin malkasisia to, minikoa dao mavail dingki-taki maponsia Lan-i, asa to mapithas ispishaiap. Mais okang nasaohabas vailan mas dingki-taka hai, asa Pankalkalan sidoh to saisan.
english: I will also direct relevant agencies to present an investigative report on the decision-making process of nuclear waste storage on Orchid Island. Before finding a permanent solution for the nuclear waste, we will provide the Yami tribe appropriate compensation.

bnn: Kanasia sahosbo Tangavolan sidoh, asa mosohis habas to sidoh, isia siva boan macion hanian to tanangaos, napalioni saicin to kanadan dailaz, mahto Tangavolan sidoh sohaisan mas nao to ana inaicia to kinli mas ngan.
english: At the same time, under the principle of respecting the Pingpu ethnic group's self- identity, and recognizing their identity, we will examine relevant laws before September 30 of this year, so that Pingpu ethnic group identity will receive the rights and status it deserves.

bnn: Painsanancin to 11 boan 1 hanian, nakitngab kata kozakoza, mapishaiap kaitdadan Incomin sidoh to dalah. Asang-Bonon to dailaz hai kitngabin, aipincin Incomin sidoh to salin-anak hai, namomoslot minsia. Namapibiskav mas sahosbon Incomin sidoh to "Incomin sidoh salin-anak to dailaz," "Incomin sidoh dalah mas ningav to dailaz," "Incomin sidoh mapacingna haling to dailaz," maponsia Lipoing ispatopa.
english: On November 1 of this year, we will begin to delineate and announce indigenous traditional territories and lands. The system of tribal public corporation is already in place. In the future, the ideals of indigenous self-government will be realized step by step. We will step up the pace and submit for legislative deliberation three laws of great importance to indigenous peoples: the Indigenous Peoples Self-Government Law, the Indigenous Peoples Land and Sea Areas Law, and the Indigenous Languages Development Law.

bnn: Aip to minaonin, namoso mas-anpok tasto kokka Incomin sidoh to palihansiap. Isia moanpokcia, sopah ito seho nakozakozaon istaho. Kaopa painsanan to 8 boan 1 hanian, Sincongin hai namapishaiap tasto Taioan to bonon mas kinozkozan to sao isain. Namapinsia Incomin sidoh to kanadan, mapinsia Incomin sidoh mailanhabas to mantok, mapinsia kanadan Incomin sidoh salin-anak, sain hai ito seho maitao napinsiaon to akitmataon.
english: Later this afternoon, we will convene a national indigenous peoples administrative meeting. In that meeting, the government will elaborate on the policies. On every August 1 to come, the Executive Yuan will report to the indigenous peoples our progress on restoring historical justice and transitional justice. To implement the Indigenous Peoples Basic Law, to serve indigenous historical justice, and to lay the foundation for indigenous self- government - these are the three major goals for the government's policy towards indigenous peoples.

bnn: Taodaniv saikin mas isaincin, itanangaos sia tilibi sinmas sasado katokato iskakaopa to Incomin kaviaz, maciskon kata malsisivit. Ni kamo napaidan mas sinkozakoza. Mahtoang kamo mainson, tahotaho, mahto seho mapinsia mas sintotopa, mamantok to kahna maisna habas to painlivaan.
english: To all of our indigenous friends here and watching on TV and online: I invite you to stand witness. I invite you not to endorse, but to oversee. Please keep pressure on the government and right its course where necessary, so that it will realize its commitments and right historical wrongs.

bnn: Matonaskal saikin mas iskaopakaopa to Incomin kaviaz, mo maipinkailas kokkacin iskaopakaopa to bonon, kandapanan to dalah, sinmas mailanhabas to is-ihomis hai oka mahto laovaiv, asa sain to samashaingan.
english: I want to thank all of our indigenous friends. You remind everyone in this country that there is irreplaceable value in the land we tread on and the traditions we inherit. This value deserves dignity.

bnn: Namapakasia kaimin sinkozakoza, naniin maikikingna sinmas katsia dalahcin to sidohsidoh is-okan mas halinga, is-okan mas aldidipaon to iliskinon, niin pasipoltav mas an-anak to bongka, naniin maldaok to isia annak-anak to dalah taimazavmazav.
english: In the future, we will push for policies to ensure that succeeding generations of indigenous tribes and all ethnic peoples in Taiwan never lose their languages and memories, that they are never separated from their cultural traditions, and that never again are they lost in a land of their own.

bnn: Tosingav saikin to mahtoang kata maciskon, sahal imita maisna habas to inihomisan, sahal imita to dalah, sahal amin imita vaivi sidoh to bongka. Mai-aopa mapakasial, mai-aopa moskon mihomis malisvala maidaza, taskon mai-aopa Taioan to alngangasan.
english: I call upon our entire society to come together and get to know our history, get to know our land, and get to know the cultures of our many ethnic peoples. Let us work towards reconciliation, a shared existence and shared prosperity, and a new future for Taiwan.

bnn: Tasingav saikin tasto Taioan to bonon, kanasia aip to haniancin, maciskon macintamasaz mapin- oni kokkatan mamantok mapiszang, vaivivaivi sidoh hai mapaloszang amin.
english: I call upon all citizens to seize the opportunities offered by this day - to join together, work hard, and build a country of justice, a country of true diversity and equality.

bnn: aiza isian sia lodon maz a monhohoma maz a bonon.
english: On the mountain, there is a farmer.

bnn: ong at adii a mabananaz a tainihoma hai.
english: And then there is a boy on his fields.

bnn: kodadaza saia sia sinsoaz saicia izok.
english: He went up to the pomelos cultivated by him.

bnn: a sisiza mas ong to laas cia.
english: He kept on plucking the fruit.

bnn: ansainon saicia sia andadaan to mahaiav mahaiav to iahlop.
english: He put them in the bag meant for packaging.
He put them down in the basket.

bnn: at aiza maz a minohalhal maz a sia to izok a hai izaon saicia.
english: Then there are the pomelos plucked by him, dropped on the ground.

bnn: minsoma tacini sasaipok sidi a a bonon maiskos mas a sidi anghaib.
english: A person who is rearing a goat passes by with it.

bnn: a maz a sidi a hai asa mosohis maon mas a izok to siniza sia kalala a.
english: The goat wants to go back to eat the pomelos that had been plucked and put inside the basket.

bnn: haito iskosa s tainisidi cia modaan.
english: But it is pulled away by his master.

bnn: aip in cin hai minsoma tacini a mabananaz a ovaaz tontampo.
english: Later, a boy rides a bike over here.

bnn: minnasian sia avadii to ai sin sin ai a minnasian sia kalala to daingia s izok cia.
english: He gets to where the baskets with pomelos are.

bnn: maz a maz a ovaaz a hai islongho sakaivakaiva.
english: The child rests and looks around.

bnn: sado saia to maz a tainiizok a hai idadaza sia lokis cia.
english: He sees the tangerine guy up in the tree.

bnn: kaz saia miliskin to ka minsooz tanghaio to tas to kalala mas izok cia.
english: He even thinks about stealing a basket of pomelos.

bnn: ong at pisialon saicia tampo at ansahanon saicia tas to kalala izok a mapondaza sia tampo.
english: Then he adjusts his bike and puts a basket of pomelos on his bike.

bnn: ong at paonang cia saicia tanghaio a modaan tondaza sia tampo cia.
english: He stole it for the time being and rides his bike away.

bnn: maponahtong a naia hai cibiskavan a isaicia tamoong at.
english: They bumped into each other roughly, and his hat was dropped off.

bnn: sakakiiv a saia sado hai nii saia haiap to aiza maz a bato itanangaos.
english: He looked back, knowing nothing about the stone ahead.

bnn: paptoha s taontaon to tanpo cia at at saia todii hai pantonghaz mototo amin a maz a izok.
english: The bicycle hit the stone on the wheel. Then he fell off his bike, and the pomelos were spilt out.

bnn: at panlanglang isaicia maz a sia bantas a.
at oninang aiza tatao maz a ovaaz isian sia silasdaan cia todii sado to mocingkol saia hai adii a tatao ovaaz hai mindangaz.
english: Fortunately, three kids in the street saw him tripping over himself then. They went helping him.

bnn: at mindia mas izok cia kaidosaan naicia kalala mapondaza sia tanpo cia.
english: Picking up pomelos, two moved the basket onto the bike.

bnn: at omano s ovaaz cia bato makonasia silasdaan.
english: The kid put the stone away the street.

bnn: ong at adii a ovaaz a taininghaio s izok a hai 'alakan saicia tampo a at pis'aika'aika opa at panmang a nadado madahpa bantas aopa panmangmang masa mocingkol.

Maqlis naipi, maqto vanaqon to tikis?

english: $30 for the cookies, anything else you need?
Can I borrow money from you?
Yes! How much do you need?

english: I forgot to bring money, can I borrow money from you?
I don't have any money either!

bnn: Panpongol saak madas soi, maqto saak simol so'oan soi?
english: I forgot to bring money, can I borrow money from you?

Maqto saak simol isoo to patasan?
Pasimoli'ang saak isoo to sozainsia qai?

Okay, but you have to give it back to me tomorrow.

english: It's raining, I don't have an umbrella, can you lend me your umbrella?

bnn: Mohaz inaak tas'a talolong. Moskon ata talolongan.

bnn: Ma'aq isoo asa'on sadoo patasan, topa'i saak.
english: You can tell me what else you want to read.

bnn: Nito mako'aq, todiip i haiza'in isoo soi.
english: It's okay, you can talk about it when you have money.

bnn: Lako'aq aso masoqis sinimol so'o to soi?
english: When are you going to pay me back?
I'll return it to you tomorrow.

bnn: Lako'aq aso masoqis sinimol so'o to patasan?
english: When are you going to return my book?

bnn: Topa i soqaisonin zako so'oan takna?
english: Didn't I return it to you yesterday?

english: Did Lian lend you this pen?
Yes, I borrowed it from him today.
Did you borrow this pen from Masau?
No, this is what mom bought.

english: We are out of salt, let's go borrow some from Mua.

english: Go tell Savung to give me my money back.
How much does she owe you?
I'm going to plant vegetables in the garden.

english: There's too much grass, I'm cutting it, I'll have to water it later.

bnn: Siza'i kaol siin tangaa pinaak qai?
english: Will you get my scythes and hoes, please?
Put it next to the plow rake.
Did you turn over the soil?
I just turned over the soil, and so on to sow seeds.

bnn: Maqto'in sinsoaz so'o to sanglavon koloton?
english: Are your vegetables ready to be harvested?

bnn: Maqto'in a tamana koloton, ni'ang a tao'las maqto kazkazon.
english: The cabbages here are ready to harvest, but the turnips there are not yet ready to harvest.
Wow! You dug up so many gourds.
Will you help me with the barn?
We're releasing fishing nets to catch fish.
The fish basket has been full of fish.
How do you usually catch fish?
I shoot fish with a spear.
Do you know how to hunt with a bow and arrow?

bnn: Makosia saak haqo malhaqo, minton madas bosol mapo'aso.
english: I usually catch my prey with a trap, but occasionally I hunt with a gun and a dog.
This is the road the boar took.

bnn: Isia naipi vanis to dapan, paaqpon isia naipi vanis to inondadanan.
english: These are the footprints of the boar, so this is the path the boar took.

bnn: Mahiqiv ata haqo, maszang haiza'in tishaqo.
english: Go and see our trap, for it seems that we have caught our prey.
The dog seems to have smelled it. Let's follow them.

bnn: Matas'i saak islabantiq, isdamo ki tanpahokaz.
english: This is a stone trap, used to catch rats.
What is that thing you put there?

bnn: Sia naipa lismosqot to haqo, ismosqot i sakot.
english: It was a leg-rigged rope trap, and we used it to catch Shankiang.

bnn: Matomasqing Tama-diqanin, madia haip to qinanop.
english: Thanks to the blessing of our ancestors, we had a great harvest today.

bnn: Uo ai! Dason mita mon'asang mapisihal mapaqosil.
english: Yeah! Let's take it back to the tribe and share it!

bnn: Na masnava saak mo-o haip sia takilibos to miniqomis a toko-oq is malasBonon.
english: I will teach everyone all kinds of animals in Bunun language today.

bnn: Na masnava saak mo-o haip sia kononkonon a toko-oq is malasBonon.
english: I will teach everyone all kinds of fruits in Bunun language today.

bnn: Masnanava, sipongol saak madas i petasan.
english: Teacher, I didn't bring my textbook.

bnn: Moskona isisils so-o to issoszangan sadoo petasan.
english: Share the book with your classmate next to you.

bnn: Mobitqos in naak a ispapatas a.
Handii naak isqaqesqes a, siza-i makosia.
english: I will lend you my eraser.

bnn: Na mal-oo in ata, asa mananolo kis modandaan monlomaq in!
english: It is the end of the class, be careful on your way home.

bnn: Na mal-oo in ata, na pasaqna in is.
english: The class is over, goodbye everyone.

bnn: Ma-aq saak a topa-on to Pima, manahip mapasadoo mo-o.
english: Hello everyone, my name is Pima.

bnn: Ma-aq saak a topa-on to Banitol, manahip mapasadoo mo-o.
english: Hello everyone, my name is Banitul.

bnn: Ma-aq saak a topa-on to Pima, manahip mapasadoo so-o.
Pima, manahip mapasadoo so-o, ma-aq saak a topa-on to Dosqav.
Ma-aq saak a topa-on to Banitol, manahip mapasadoo so-o.
Banitol, manahip mapasadoo so-o, ma-aq saak a topa-on to Dosqav.
Ma-aq saak a issia Banga to tina, topa-on naak ngaan to Poni.
Ma-aq saak a issia Banga to nobano-az topa-on naak ngaan to Savi.
english: I am Banga's sister. My name is Savi.

bnn: Inaak nepa masnanava, topa-on sia ta ngaan to Biong.
Inaak nepa masitoqas, topa-on nepa to Tiang.
Simaq a topa-on to Pima ka?
Simaq a topa-on to Dosqav a?
Ma-aq a Dosqav a inaak kaviaz.

english: What is your elder sister's name?

bnn: Topa-on naak masitoqas ngaan to Abos.
english: My elder sister's name is Abus.
What is your younger sister's name?

bnn: Topa-on naak masinoba ngaan to Samingaz.
english: My younger sister's name is Samingaz.

bnn: Dooq maqansiap aso issia ta ngaan?
Piaq in so-o masitoqas sia ta qamisan?
english: How old is your elder brother?

bnn: Piaq in so-o masinoba sia ta qamisan?
english: How old is your younger brother?
Do you have schools in your community?

bnn: Ihaan aso iso-o asang to pasnanava-an ta isnava-an?
english: Do you study in your tribe's school?

bnn: Uo, maszang saam tastolomaq is isnava-an haan pasnanava-an.
english: Yes, we are like family while we are studying at school.
No, he is my younger brother's friend.

bnn: Ni-i, issia nepa masinoba naak to kaviaz.
english: No, he is my younger brother's friend.

bnn: Ni-i, issia nepa nobananaz naak to pakasvala-an.
english: No, he is my younger brother's friend.
No, she is my younger sister.
No, she is my younger sister.
How many people in their family?
There are five people in their family.
How many children in your family?
There are four children in our family.
How many younger siblings do you have?

bnn: Uka naak a nobananaz, losqa to heza-an saak tatao ka nobano-az.
english: I don't have any younger brothers, but I have three younger sisters.
How many older siblings do you have?
I don't have any older siblings.
How many siblings do you have?

bnn: Kamamakazhav a diqanin a, asa to maqasmav qoo danombaqis.
english: It's a bit cold, so you need to drink more warm water.

bnn: Kamamaklang a diqanin a, asa to qoqoo danom.
english: It's a bit hot, so you need to drink more water.

bnn: Madaing a vali ka, asa mananolo to biaq is pasanvali-on.
english: The sun is bright and remember to wear sunscreen.

bnn: Madia ka lohom a, oka vali sado-an.
english: There are a lot of clouds but no sun in the sky.

bnn: Na oka vali kis koton in i, madia ka lohom a, madaing amin a lovlov a.
english: It will be cloudy and windy but not sunny tomorrow.
How was the weather that day?

bnn: Makazhavkazhav haip diqanin a, asa menok panhapavon to holos is monnata.
english: It was a bit cold and you needed to wear a jacket when you went outside.

bnn: Mako-aq diqanin to mal-oo to todiip a?
english: How's the weather on the weekend?

bnn: Masihal a diqanin to mal-oo to todiip.
english: It will be sunny on the weekend.
Will it be rainy that day?

bnn: Na masihal todiip a diqanin, na ni-i to qodanan.
english: It will have no rain and be sunny that day.

bnn: Uo, na qodanan is todiip in.
english: Yes, it will be rainy that day.

bnn: Isdangza in, minsoma in a vali.
english: The rain stops and the sun comes out.

bnn: Qodanan in, ni-i saak minadas i talolong.
english: It is raining and I don't have an umbrella with me.

bnn: Ni-i in qodanan lopa ka dao, na qodanan is tonqovali in, asa madas i talolong is monnata.
english: It is not raining now, but it will be rainy in the afternoon, so you need to bring an umbrella when you go out.

bnn: Na makazhav is pongna in to qamisan?
english: Will it be very cold in winter next year?

bnn: Na makazhav is pongna in to qamisan, asa panmadia holos is menok.
english: Yes, it will be very cold in winter next year, so you need to put on extra layers.

bnn: Na maklang haip is talabal in to diqanin?
english: Will it be very hot in summer this year?

bnn: Uo, asa maqasmav is qoo danom i maklang is talabal in to todiip.
english: Yes, it will be very hot and you need to drink more water.

bnn: Mazima saak is namintalabal in, mopa mananqat a diqanin a.
english: I like spring because the weather is warm.

bnn: Ni-i saak mazima namimqamisan in to diqanin, mopa madia balivosan.
english: I don't like autumn because there are lots of typhoons in autumn.

I will share it with you.
I forgot to bring the eraser.
Do you forget to bring your pen?

bnn: Uo, pasimolav ang saak iso-o ispapatas?
english: Yes, can you lend me a pen?

bnn: Na ma-aq so-o asa-on ma-on is tonqovali in?
english: What would you like for lunch?

bnn: Na ma-aq so-o asa-on ma-on is sanavan in?
english: What would you like for dinner?
What did you have for breakfast?

bnn: Sia nibo ta naak a konon.
Ma-aq so-o konon to ma-on in petotonqovali?
english: What did you have for lunch?

bnn: Ngaosa ang aso, na kilimok aso kis onis in.
english: You go first and I will catch up later.

bnn: Ni-i, na tangos ang ata ansaqan petasan.
english: No, we have to carry books first.

bnn: Ni-i ang, masinav ang saak baloko.
english: Not yet. I am doing the dishes.
Did you rinse out your mouth?
Yes, I rinsed out my mouth.

bnn: Mavia aso ni-i ang tel-ima to?
english: Why didn't you wash your hands?

bnn: Na tal-ima saak is onin in.

english: What are you going to do after school?

bnn: Na malkama-aq nepa kis mal-oo in?
english: What is she doing after school?
She is going to go dancing.

english: Aping is not at home. I am Ilung. What can I do for you? I will let him know when he comes back.

bnn: Qodas, Abos i Aping saam, to-av ang hilav on!
english: Grandma, we are Abus and Aping, please open the door for us.
I am Lumav, I am here for Vilian.
Grandma, I am here to see you.

bnn: Talmadia ni-i sasado-an to, masalpodengaz saak so-o.
english: You haven't been here for a long time. I missed you so much.
Aping, I am here to play with you.
Come on in! I have been waiting for you for a long time.

english: This is the sweet potato I grow. Try it!
The sweet potato is so sweet.

bnn: Hanoin! inaak nepi sinsoaz to kononkonon, siza-i tanam ma-on.
english: Come here! These are the fruits I grow. You should try it.

bnn: Malonqo-a ti! Tanam ma-on i inaak sinsoaz ni-i to pa-iho-an to po-i kon!
english: Take a seat! You should try some organic corn that I grow.

bnn: Ehi! Madavosdengaz a po-i kon konon to.
english: Wow! The corn tastes so sweet.

bnn: Ni-i saak maqto ma-on izok si-a-av i salvi ta.
english: I can't eat oranges. I will have some apples instead.
Sure, I like it very much.

bnn: Masala saak kononkonon i na konon so-o.
english: Let me peel the fruit for you.

bnn: Unin ang, madia voos konon a kononkonon on.
english: Thank you. This fruit is so juicy.
I will bring you some water.

bnn: pinmade-av ma-on, madia naak a sinhanat pan-e-an.
english: Enjoy yourself. I cooked a lot of dishes.

bnn: Ehi! Toza to mahansomdengaz amin masihaldengaz is konon.
english: Oh! It smells good and looks delicious.

bnn: pinmade-av ma-on, madiadengaz ang a na maqto konon on.
english: Enjoy yourself. There is a lot more.

bnn: pinmade-av ma-on, madiadengaz ang a na maqto konon on.
english: Enjoy yourself. There are plenty here.

bnn: Madia in naak a konon a, las-opa-an in saak.
english: I ate a lot and couldn't eat any more.
I will take you to the mountains today.

bnn: Topa tina to madia dao haan lodon ta qatibing.
english: Mom says that there are lots of mosquitoes in the mountains.

bnn: Na dasok amo monhaan qoma ta.
english: I will take you to the fields.
Are we going to loosen the soil?
Teacher will take us to the riverside.
Teacher will take us to the mountains today.
Are we going to the riverside today?

bnn: Ni-i, na dason ata masnanava ta monlodon.
english: No, our teacher is going to take us to the mountains.
Are we going to the mountains today?

bnn: Ni-i, na monhaan ata qoma haip.
english: No, we are going to the fields.

bnn: Masnanava, na ma-aq mita lopa ko ka kilimon haan vanglaz ta sadoo haip?
english: Teacher, what are we going to see at the riverside?
We are going to see dragonflies.

bnn: Masnanava, na ma-aq mita kilimon sadoo haan lodon ta?
english: Teacher, what are we going to see in the mountains?
We are going to see butterflies.

bnn: Na malkama-aq ata moohaan qoma ta to?
english: What are we going to do in the fields?

bnn: Na monhaan ata qoma ta sadoo imita sinsoaz to po-i ka, asa mananolo kis heza qaloa siin baqosaz minsoma!
english: We are going to see the corn we grow in the fields, but you need to be aware of the ants and bees.
Teacher, are we going to swim in the river?

bnn: Ni-i, na kilim ata salinbonoaz ta.
english: No, we are going to see dragonflies.

bnn: Masnanava, na monhaan ata qoma minang i sanglav?
english: Teacher, are we going to grow some vegetables in the fields?
We are going to loosen the soil today.

bnn: Lopa ang saak sadoo mamangtok miqomis ang to salinbonoaz.
english: Today is the first time I see real living dragonflies.

bnn: Hia! Mazima saak talikoan i mano-azdengaz is sado-an.
english: Yeh! Wow! I love butterflies. They are very beautiful.
Those are not butterflies. They are bees.

bnn: Iti-a maqasivong, ka-a to mazavmazav mondaqvisan ta!
english: Come here and take a look. Don't go too far!

bnn: Uo, na ni-i saam mondaqvisan ta.
english: Got it, we won't go anywhere too far.

bnn: Ka-a to tindangkol iti, modaokdaok kis modandaan biaq is na motinkol.
english: Don't run and walk slowly lest you fall down.
I want to see them right away.
How do you go to the block-house?
How does he go to the hospital?

english: How do you go to Penghu?

bnn: Na tonkosbabai saak is monPonghoo ta.
english: I go to Penghu by plane.

bnn: Na tonqato saak is monPonghoo ta.
english: I go to Penghu by boat.

bnn: Na tonma-aq aso kis monlomaq in?
Na tonlehlemohiav saak kis monlomaq in.
Tonma-aq a Tanivo kis monpasnanava-an ta?
english: How does Tanivu go to school?
Tanivu goes to school by train.

bnn: Tonma-aq a Manias is monhaan odidinonan ta?
english: How does Manias go to church?

bnn: Tontonton a Manias is monhaan odidinonan ta.
english: Manias goes to church by bicycle.
Do you go to school by MRT?

bnn: Ni-i, tonlehlebonon saak is monpasnanava-an ta.
english: No, I go to school by bus.
Do you go to school by bicycle?

bnn: Uo, tontonton saak is monpasnanava-an ta.
english: Yes, I go to school by bicycle.
Do you go to Kaohsiung by High Speed Rail?

bnn: Uo, tonlehleqovias saak is monTakao ta.
english: Yes, I go to Kaohsiung by High Speed Rail.

bnn: Dooq tonlehlesapoz nait tonkosbabai aso kis monhaan Posong ta?
english: Are you going to Taitung by train or by plane?

bnn: Tonkosbabai saak, mopa sia kis tonkosbabai ka mataliskang i tonlehlesapoz ton.
english: I will take the plane because it is faster than the train.

bnn: Dooq tonlehlebonon nait tonlehle aso kis monhaan odidinonan ta?
english: Are you going to drive to the church or take the bus?

bnn: Tonlehle saak is monhaan odidinonan ta, mopa sia kis tonlehle ka kamamadozong i tonlehlehbonon ton.
english: I will drive to the church because it is more convenient than the bus.

bnn: Meshoan so-o lomaq i babalivan to dangi-an?
english: Is the market close to your house?

bnn: Ni-i, kadadaok saak tontontondengaz monhaan babalivan ta.
english: No, it is not, so I always ride the motorcycle to the market.

bnn: Dooq meshoan a sasato-an pinonhahaqil i pasnanava-an ta?
english: Is the post office close to the school?
Yes, it is within walking distance.

bnn: Dooq meshoan a kakonanqesing i papando-an ta?
english: Is the restaurant close to the station?

bnn: Mesnapapando-an ta ka tan-anak ang a na heza to himatektek maqto tonadiip.
english: It only takes five minutes after you walk out of the station.
I would like to visit you.

bnn: Uka saak ilomaq i heza naak a na asa-on palkada-an. Na moqna in is.
english: I am out today. How about another day?

bnn: Dooq heza so-o el-o-an is koton in? Na kilim saak so-o kis tonqovali in.
english: Then, are you available tomorrow? I'll visit you tomorrow afternoon.

bnn: Uo, na ilomaq saak maltatala so-o.
english: Sure, I will wait for you at home.

bnn: Dooq maqto saak siza qalinga? Na asa saak matsolot mapatas.
english: Would you mind if I do the voice recording? I would like to keep a record.

bnn: Dooq maqto siza ki bisokbisok to qaningo?
english: Would you mind if I do the video recording?

bnn: Azoq ni-i, mopa ni-i ang saak mapinqala, ni-i ang amin patqemansotan a sankonan.
english: No, I am plain and the warehouse hasn't been tidied up yet.

bnn: Uo, na losqa saak siza qaningo.
english: Then I will just take photos.

bnn: Azoq amin ni-i to siza-an i qaningo.
Unin so-o ki maqto ang mon-iti pababazbaz.
english: Thank you for accepting the interview.

bnn: Ni-i to miko-aq, ma-aq so-o asa-on istopa?
english: You are welcome. What would you like to know?

bnn: Taqo-av ang to malkamama-aq aso to mendodo-az ang?
english: What do you do when you are young?

bnn: Makakeval saak to qabas ang, losqa to papal-o-on in saak.
english: I was a police officer but I am retired now.

bnn: Dooq heza so-o lopa ko ka palkada-an to kozkoza-on?
english: Then, are you working at the moment?

bnn: Dooq kathaan amin ovavaz-az so-o ki asang ti?
english: Do your kids live in the tribe too?

bnn: ni-i, ma-aq ovavaz-az naak a kathaan asangdengaz ta.
english: No, my kids are all living in the city.
Then, do you live by yourself?

bnn: Heza naak sinepok to tas-a aso siin tas-a qazam, maszang saam i tastolomaq.
english: I also keep a dog and a bird. They are my family.

bnn: Heza naak amin sinepok naong to tas-a, ni-i to maqanimolmol is heza sinapok a oskonan.
english: I have a cat too. I won't get bored with the company of my pet.

bnn: Asa saak masingav so-o ki pali-oni qanop to is-atosasamo.
english: I would like to ask you about the taboos of hunting.

bnn: Ni-i saak maqansiap a, ma-aq is heza naak qansepon a na taqo-ak aso.
english: I don't know much about that, but I will tell you everything I know.

bnn: ma-aq sia isqaqanop to qemangsot a heza maqma-aq to samo?
english: Do you have any taboos about hunting weapons?

bnn: Ma-aq naam iskokosia qanop to qemangsot a ni-i ka binano-az on maqto matidoo.
english: Our hunting weapons are untouchable to women.

bnn: Dooq maqto ka binano-az on taskon qanop?
english: Then, can women go hunting together?

bnn: Ni-i, ni-i ka binano-az on maqto qanop.
english: No, women cannot go hunting either.

bnn: Manias mondipa-a ang mabaliv i davostilas i, oka in mita davostilas.
english: Manias, our home is out of rice wine, please go and buy some.

bnn: Heza ang haan pipit-e-an ta to tas-apaan, ka-a in mabaliv!
english: There is still one bottle left in the kitchen, so there is no need to buy one!

bnn: Mavai kis losqa tas-apaan, matikhiva ang mabaliv to dosapaan.
english: One bottle is not enough for me, go and buy two more back.

bnn: Heza mo-o davostilas? na asa saak mabaliv.
english: I am looking for rice wine. Do you have any rice wine?

bnn: Heza! Na piaq so-o balivon to?
english: Yes! How many bottles do you need?

bnn: Na mabaliv saak dosapaan to davostilas, heza ang sia tilas to tastobotiqo.
english: I want two bottles and a pack of rice.

bnn: Handii ka tilas on, heza ang so-o na asa-on mabaliv?
english: Here is the rice, what else do you need?

bnn: Asa saak mabaliv i nibo, heza?
english: I want some eggs too, do you have some?

bnn: Uka in a nibo, aminon in doma mabaliv.

english: I want to buy some clothes.
What kind of clothes do you like?

bnn: Sia naak holospotol a asa-on mabaliv.
english: I want to buy the clothes with short sleeves.

bnn: Heza ang naam a madoqlas amin malenqas.
english: We have white and blue ones too.

bnn: Si-a-av i malenqas holos to tas-a.
english: Please give me the clothes in blue.

bnn: Manias, se-isaq aso sangan ang? pistalboqtalboq aso?
english: Manias, where have you been just now? Did you go exercising?

bnn: Ni-i, mindangaz saak qodas naak mapababaliv sanglav ton.
english: No, I went grocery shopping for my grandma.

bnn: Mopa ta qan a, Dooq heza so-o al-o-an is sanavan in? Koskon ata ma-on i petosanavan.
english: No wonder! Are you available at night? Would you like to have a meal with me?

bnn: Na ni-i to maqto ki, na mabaliv ang saak holos.
english: No, I want to buy some clothes.
Then, I will go with you.

bnn: Temibabalivan, piaq soidaing a sanglav on tas-alinoqos is balivon?
english: Hello, how much is this bunch of vegetables?

bnn: Maposansoidaing a sanglav is tas-a linoqos balivon.
english: The vegetables are $20 for a bunch.

bnn: Piaq soidaing a hotan is balivon?
english: How much are these sweet potatoes?

bnn: Mati-onsoidaing is tas-atingting a hotan balivon.
english: Sweet potatoes are thirty dollars for a pound.

bnn: Siza saak sanglav to dosalinoqos heza ang hotan to tas-atingting.
english: Please give me two bunches of vegetables and a pound of sweet potatoes.

bnn: Manias, pasimolav ang saak iso-o to ispapatas, mopa sipongol saak madas i ispapatas?
english: Manias, I forgot to bring my pen. Can you lend me one?

bnn: Uka naak amin, issia nepi Tanivo ton.
english: I don't have one either. This is Tanivu's.

bnn: Pasimolav ang saak to mohiav, na kavava-ak masoqis.
english: Can you lend me the pen for a second? I will return to you immediately.

bnn: Unin ang, taqo-av a Tanivo to onin ang amin.
english: Thank you and thank Tanivu for me.
I want to return these two books.

bnn: Uo, heza ang so-o na asa-on?
english: No problem and what else do you need?

bnn: Asa ang saak simol tao to petasan.
english: I would like to borrow these three books.

bnn: Handii amin, ka-a to sipongol masoqis is talti-on in.
english: Sure and remember to return them after three days.

bnn: I-isaq naak a isqaqesqes a? ni-i ang aso mesoqis.
english: You haven't returned me the eraser.

bnn: Mavia naak isqaqesqes to is-oka to.
english: Then, why is my eraser missing?

bnn: Dooq is ispasimol in so-o ki Manias ta.
english: Did you lend it to Manias?

bnn: Na niap qo, na topa-ok nepa.
english: I don't know. I will go and ask her.

bnn: Tangosa siza inaak isqaqesqes ton maqesqes.
english: I will lend you my eraser first.

bnn: Tanivo, dooq sia Manias ta pesimol so-o pakahapavon to holos ton?
english: Tanivu, did Manias lend you this coat?

bnn: Ni-i, sia tina naak a mebaliv penaak.
english: No, my mom bought it for me.

bnn: Mamaszang mo-o sia Manias ta pakahapavon to holos to.
english: Manias's coat is the same as yours.

bnn: Ni-i naam a patas mamaszang, mataqdong sia ta pakahapavon to holos sado-an.
english: His coat is black, so our colors are different.

bnn: Tanivo, sinimol aso sia Manias to soi?
english: Tanivu, did you borrow money from Manias?

bnn: Uo, al soqesok nepa haip dao ka, losqa to sipongol saak madas i soi.
english: Yes, I was supposed to return to him today, but I forgot to bring the money.
Then, when will you return the money?

bnn: Na soqesok pesia ta kis koton in.
english: I will return to him tomorrow.

bnn: Uo, na topa-ok a Manias a.
english: Okay, I will tell Manias for you.

bnn: Ma-aq is malhaqo ki qamotis a asa to makosia haqoqato ta, ma-aq is malhaqo ki tikolas a asa to makosia haqomosqot ta. mopa ta mamantok.
english: It is correct to catch mice through rangay and catch bamboo partridges through qjiulang.

bnn: Mopa ta qan a dao, paaq po-on ni-i saak odamo-an i moliva naak a sinpalhaqo ka.
english: No wonder! I am mistaken and that's why I cannot catch any of them.

bnn: Na masnava ang saak so-o to na piko-oq a sia dii dosa haqo kon is malhaqo.
english: Then I will teach you how to set up these two traps.

bnn: Uo, toza to onin so-o, na madia naak tesaq is qabas in.
english: Great! I will be able to catch the prey in the future.

bnn: Masmoav madaqvasdengaz in a ismoot haan qoma ta, mondipa-a siza kaol haan patqemangsotan ta, na monhaan ta qoma ta mavalval i ismoot.
english: The grass in the fields is too tall. Go to the warehouse to take the sickle and let's go to the fields.

bnn: Isisila haan kalala ta, osado-an is monkonbo in patqemangsotan ta.
english: It is next to the round basket. You will see it when you enter the warehouse.

bnn: Asa to Mananolo kis ankos i kaol i, manosqitdengaz a kaol a, ka-a to siszaqan.
english: Be careful and don't get hurt. The sickle is very sharp.

bnn: Ka-a to kadapan inaak sinpalhaqo ka!
Ihaan lokis nasto ta naak a sinpalhaqo ka.
english: My trap is under that tree.

bnn: Mavia aso to maqansiap ang to?
Heza naak i-iti ka sinpasqaal a, paaq po-on maqansiap ang saak to i-isaq naak a sinpalhaqo ka.
english: I make a mark here, so I know where my trap is.

bnn: Ma-aq dii kalala kon a topa-on to mat-iskaan, pihanon zami vanglaz ta patala ki iskaan.
english: This is a fish trap which we put beside the river for fishing.

bnn: Uka naam iti mat-iskaan to kalala, makosia saam ispalalaskan is malaskan.
english: We don't have any fish traps there, so we catch fish with a fishing rod.

bnn: Ni-i saak mekosia ispalalaskan a, dooq maqto ang pasnava zako kis moqnin?
english: I have never used a fishing rod before, would you mind teaching me next time?

bnn: Na maqto! taskon ata malaskan is moqna in.
english: Sure! Let's go fishing together next time.

bnn: Na zako ka masnava so-o matas-i ki mat-iskaan to kalala ka.
english: I will teach you how to make a fish trap next time.

bnn: Hia! Bizakbizak in so-o ka ispalalaskan a, dooq heza iskaan ma-on! kavava-i silolo.
english: Your fishing rod is moving. Isn't the fish on the hook? Pull it up!

bnn: Mal-o-ang i, masmoav in a qato to vialvialdengaz a, i-iti saak silolo ispalalaskan to doon a, mondipa-a aso siza salozo ta.
english: Wait, the ship is rolling heavily. I am here to pull the fishing rod and you should go there to grab me the net.

bnn: Silolo-av ang a iskaan maponzako-an, na zako in a mindangaz so-o silolo.
english: Pull the fish to my side and I will help you pull it up.

bnn: Toza to manahipdengaz a is-aang ai madia mita tesaq, matmoz amin a is-olading i iskaan to kalala kon.
english: Great! It is a bumper crop today with full fish baskets.

bnn: Ina, kavava-a ata mosoqis monlomaq i, na ispasiqto ki mita doma.
english: Let's go back immediately and share it with everyone.
Stop playing and quickly sit in your seat.

bnn: Malkahima haip, pal'o'on laqbinga, moskon ata monata modadaan.
english: It's Friday today, we have a day off tomorrow. Let's go out and play together!
Great! Let's go to the riverside.
What day will it be tomorrow?

bnn: Malkatao laqbing, pismali ata laqbing mina'on tongqovali.
english: Tomorrow will be Wednesday. Let's go play ball tomorrow afternoon!
What will you be doing tomorrow morning?

bnn: Niciobi laqbing, na moskon saak tina monhaan kiokai.
english: Tomorrow will be Sunday, I will be going to church with my mom.

bnn: Monhaanang saak patakiani, asa saak motaq.
english: I feel like vomiting. I need to go to the restroom.

bnn: Masnanava, asa saak monhaan patakiani, masaqbit naak tian.
english: Teacher, I have a stomachache. I need to go to the restroom.
May I go wash my hands?
It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.

bnn: Masnanava, namal'oo saak tongqovali'i, saqbit daingaz naak bongo.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.
Okay, take care and go home.

bnn: Masnanava, namal'oo saaki maoq'na malkatas'a, aopa nasadoo saak ising.
english: Teacher, I need to take a sick leave next Monday. I have to see a doctor.

bnn: Ihaan nai pataki'an, aopa saqbita tian.
english: She has a stomachache. She's in the restroom.

bnn: Masnanava, maloo a Balan haip, aopa saqbit a modan.
english: Teacher, Balan has a sore throat. She took a sick leave today.

bnn: Taqo'i saam to makoaq aso to bonon.

english: My name is Taupas Tanapima, and I'm 10 years old.
What ethnic group are you from?

bnn: Maaq saak a ito Bonon sidoq.

english: Are all your family members indigenous?

bnn: Uo, amin inaaq tastolomaq Bonon sidoq.
english: Yes, my whole family is Bunun.

bnn: Nii, Bonon a tama, Poot a tina.
english: No, my father is Bunun, and my mother is Han Taiwanese.

bnn: Maaq saak a isia Pima-Savi to o'vaz'az.
Tama soo a daiza'aa? Piaqin siata qamisan?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

bnn: Nii, maaq naipa a inaam asang to madaingaz, mavao'onin naipa.
english: No, he is an elder of our tribe. He is 80 years old.

bnn: Mastaan daingaz sia masitoqas qamisan soo?
english: Is your brother much older than you?

bnn: Talmadin nito mapasadoo, aopat moslo kaso taldaqvas'i?
english: I haven't seen you in a while. Have you grown taller?
I'm going to the office to see the teacher.
He's going to throw away the trash.

bnn: Ihaan naipa ap'ap'an ta, na pintataiv naipa o'nisin apap.
english: He's at the swimming pool. He's going to compete in a swimming competition later.

bnn: Isaq a Savi? Na patindangkol naipa o'nisin.
english: Where is Savi? She's going to compete in a running competition later.
She's in the auditorium. I'll go call her.
Let's go to the playground together.

bnn: Ngaosang saak mabaliv kaonon tongkovali, na mon'ita saak kilim soo.
english: I'll go buy lunch first, and then I'll meet you later.
Let's carry the lunch boxes together!

bnn: Kilim'a doma bonon, na kilim'ang saak sinsi.
english: You find someone else, I'm going to find the teacher.
Is Pima competing in croquet today?
No, he's competing in high jump.
Will you compete in the sports day?
What will we do in the sports day?
We will compete in tug of war.
Will we sell food at the sports day?

bnn: Nii, na babali'van ata o'o'pon-mali a.
Toza kaso to malmanano i, o'siza'an i'ci-vang!
english: Congratulations on getting first place! You're amazing!
Yes, she's sleeping in her room.

bnn: Uka, laopang nai monata, na maqmotin molomaq.
english: No, she's not. She just went out and will be back in the evening.

bnn: Ihaan nai ni-kai, monda'za'a ta kilim siata.
english: He's upstairs. You can go up and find him.

bnn: Ai! Taopas qana, Talmadin nito pasadoo, masihal aopa?
english: It's Taupas. I haven't seen you in a while! How have you been?
I'm doing great! I came to chat with you.

bnn: Ihaan nai pipit'ia'an ta makal'ing sanglav, o'na'on zako.
english: He's in the kitchen cooking. Let me go call him.

bnn: Monhaan nai patolkokan ta madamo tolkok.
english: She went to the chicken coop to catch chickens.

bnn: Uka moo qodas ilomaq, ihaan nai qoma ta, ihaan a lomaq ton mantatala.
english: Your grandfather is not at home. He's in the field. Wait for him to come back.

bnn: Talmadin nito pasadoo, moslo'in aso taldaqvas i.
english: I haven't seen you in a while. You've grown taller.

bnn: Toza to manahip sadoo soo mon'iti.
english: It's so good to see you.

bnn: Pimoo a bonglai'on, pokombo'i haan piskakazha'van ta.
english: Here's a pineapple for you. Put it in the refrigerator.

bnn: Talmadin aso nito tantongo a, na loklasok naingka amin moskon maon.
english: It's been a while. Let's have a meal together.

bnn: Azoq azaq, na moaz saaq qoo ocia, haan ata bokzavan ta pababazbaz.
english: No need to bother. I'll just have tea. Let's sit in the living room and chat.
Thank you for your hospitality. I have to go now.

bnn: Haiza laopang kinolot to tolkok'on, dasi molomaq, kasasaos'i maon.
english: This chicken was just freshly killed. Take it home and enjoy it slowly.

bnn: Dooq maqto ata pasadoo i laqbing mina'on tongqovali?
english: Can I make an appointment with you tomorrow afternoon?

bnn: Na maqto aopa ihaan kako ta? Na lasasing ata.
english: How about meeting at school? We need to shoot a video.

bnn: Azoq monhaan ata o'ampokan ta, na nokan saak ito Bonon to holos.
english: Then let's go to the community center. I'll wear folk costume.

bnn: Mastaan manao'az naam asang to dandan, saopa'a ti i maqatispong'in a dandan.
english: The cherry blossoms in our tribe are beautiful when they bloom. Come find me when the flowers bloom!

bnn: Na masmoav'in o'soii i, panhaanin maoq'na to mintalapal.
english: That would have to wait until spring. It's too late, isn't it?

bnn: Azoq ihaan'a kaso los'an manaq tainga ta mon'i'ti.
english: Then come during our Ear Festival!
Alright! I'm looking forward to it!

bnn: Tosingav soo to mavia aso to mosaoqais haan asang ti i?
english: May I ask why you decided to move back to the tribe?

bnn: Aopa asa saak ihaan asang ti masnava ovavaz'az.
english: I want to return to teach at the local school.

bnn: Viato nito sivng haan he'ci ta masnava i?
english: Why not teach in the city?

bnn: Aopa i'iti naak a is'ang, dooq na haizang tamasaz'an saipok anakanak to taisis'aan.
english: Because I miss my hometown and I also want to give back to the tribe.

bnn: Maqansiap aso matin'on'i! Simaq a masnava soo?
english: You're very skilled at weaving, who taught you?

bnn: Sia inaaq qodas-binanaoaz, siata a mastaan maqansiap matin'on laopako ihaan inaam asang.
english: It was my grandmother, she is the most skilled weaver in our tribe.

bnn: Maaq soo i'liskinan i, na asa maqansiap matin'on?
english: How did you develop an interest in learning weaving?

bnn: Maaq a matin'on'on a, isia Bonon to sin'iqomis, maaki maqansiap amin a maikikingna matin'on a, na maqto sia Bonon to sin'iqomis saoqabasqabas.
english: Weaving is a part of our culture, and I want to ensure its continuity.

bnn: Mastaan masihal qodan a davos-madoq i.
Aii! Malmanano aso! Malbobonto i ka'davos?
english: You're really talented. Does it take a long time to make?

bnn: Nii! Na moaz tasto-islongqo'an. Po'ngaos'on'ang a dolaz siin tilas pit'a'li, pada'ngi'an i tamol, pisihalon mabizoq, na maqto'in ladi'ngon haan qao'ngo.
english: No, it only takes about a week. After steaming the sticky rice and white rice, we mix it with yeast powder, and then it can be stored in a jar.

bnn: Haiza naak daqpoot siin tolkom, amin inaaq sinsoaz!
english: I have chili and lokiy, both grown by myself!

bnn: Mabaliv saak daqpoot siin tolkom, piaq soi naopata?
Madoo saak holos dii, piaq soi?
english: I like this piece of clothing. How much is it?

bnn: Masmoav maqlis, dooq maqto mavanaq to tikis?
english: It's too expensive. Can't you lower the price a bit?

bnn: Nito maqto! Maaki vanaqon a, na somasolo saak.
english: No, if I lower it further, I'll lose money.

bnn: Uo na! Sia i mataqdong a.
english: Alright then, I'll take a black piece of clothing.

bnn: Baliv saak daos siin tipin i.
english: I want this knife and this pot.

bnn: Dosa linaoqos! Inaaq naipon sintas'i, mantok to na maqto talbonto ikma'ai'on.
english: It's a total of 2000 dollars. I handmade these, and they are guaranteed to last a long time.

bnn: Dooq maqto vanaqon tikis a soi? Na pa'ok naak kaviaz to mon'iti a maba'liv.
english: I'll introduce my friend to buy. Can you give a further discount?

bnn: Uo! Na ia'soi'ok aso maposan pasento.
english: Alright! I'll give you a 20% discount.

bnn: Monhan'a dii sadoo! Haiza holos, haiza amin tamohong.
english: Come and take a look! We sell clothes and hats.

bnn: Maaki tas'a holos a, tao saba mahima'on a soi, maaki tao holos a, tas'a li'no'qos a soi.
english: One piece of clothing is 350 dollars, three pieces for 1000 dollars.

bnn: Baliv saak tas'a, sia'i baq'lo a.
english: I'll just buy one piece, please give me a new one.

bnn: Uninang! Baliv saak i dolaz siin sinhanat to titi maqav.
english: Hello, I would like to buy sticky rice and braised pork with maqaw pepper.

bnn: Ukin a qaising. haizang a tinpo'la tana, balivon soo?
english: The rice is sold out. I have tana pancakes, would you like to buy them?

bnn: Uo na! Saiving saak tas'a, na baliv saak qaising i maoqnin.
english: Alright, please give me one. I'll come back next time to buy rice.

bnn: Uo, ladi'ngon zako haan loop, mahima'on soi.
english: Okay, I'll pack it in a bag for you. That'll be 50 dollars.

bnn: Miqomisang, haip qanian na isnavak amo to toqaoq a ito Bonon kakaonon to qalinga.
english: Hello everyone. Today, I am going to teach you how to say the Bunun language for food.
Do you understand what the teacher says?

bnn: Masnanava! nii ak itqaal, Maqto moqnang bazbaz?
english: I don't understand. Can you repeat it again?

bnn: Nii ak otan-aan, Maqto pidaingon qalinga to tikis?
english: I can't hear you, can you speak louder?

bnn: Sadoa aas dii! Kinkinoza aas zako masipol.
english: Look here, please! Repeat after me.
Read it again. Please speak louder.
I forgot to bring my pen.
I forgot to bring my eraser.

bnn: Simola aas dingalan oskonan mapasnava ton isqaqaisqais.
english: Please borrow erasers from your classmates.

bnn: Na pan-iti in ata mapasnava na ihan moqnin lihai moqna mapasado.
english: Class dismissed, see you next week.

bnn: Isia aak Vilian ovaz-az, Topaon ngan to Sipal.
english: I am Vilian's son and my name is Sipal.

bnn: Isia aak Vilian ta isnanavan topaon ngan to Sipal.
english: I am a student of Vilian and my name is Sipal.

bnn: Topaon inak Tama ngan to Vilian.
Inak aipon masitoqas nanaz. Topaon ngan to Tolbos.
english: He is my brother, his name is Kolas. *[Kolas] please change the names to men of all races.

bnn: Inak aipon kaviaz, Topaon iston ngan to Sani.
english: She is my friend and her name is Sani.

bnn: Piaqin sia Tama soo haip ponsanan qamisan.
Inak Tama mahimanin qamisan haip to ponsanan.

english: How many brothers and sisters do you have?

bnn: Haiza nak dosa masitoqas, Tas-a masinaoba.
english: I have two brothers and sisters and one younger brother and sister.
How many people are in your family?

bnn: Haiza nam papat tasto lomaq Bonon.
english: There are four of us in our family.
I studied in [Hualien]. *Hualien] is free to change places.

bnn: Iso to pantamaon maaq ista kozkozaon?
english: What does your uncle do for a living?

bnn: Iso to masitoqas naoaz haiza ista kozkozaon?
english: Does your sister have a job?
Yes, but she is a Amis.
Yes, we are all very tall.
Does your sister go to school?
Do your siblings speak the language?
Yes, they speak the ethnic language.
How many brothers and sisters do you have?
I have three brothers and sisters.
Do you live with your parents?

bnn: Uo, moskon aak inak Tama Tina.
english: Yes, I live with my mom and dad.

bnn: Moskon aas iso to Aki Bai?
english: Do you live with your grandparents?
No, I didn't live with them.

bnn: Moskon aak inak Tama, Tina, Masitoqas nanaz.
english: I live with my father, mother and brother.
When are you going back to the tribe?

bnn: Maqi pal-onin aak ka mosoqis topa aak.
english: I will go back in the summer.

bnn: Ma aak ka Bonon to ovaz-az.

english: The sun is coming out, it's very hot.
Is it going to be cold outside?
It's cold, so wear more clothes.

bnn: Nii haip to mabaqis nii amin makazhav, Masihal saa.
english: It's neither cold nor hot today, very comfortable.

bnn: Uka lohom ihan diqanin, Santasal in a bintoqan.
english: There were no clouds in the sky; the stars came out.

bnn: Isdangza in, Sansoma in vali, Monhapav in qanivalval.
english: The rain has just stopped, the sun has come out, the rainbow is coming out.
What's the weather like where you are?
We're going to have a big storm here.
Very well, out of the big sun.
I have to go to school.

bnn: Makazhav a diqanin, Asa pidai-on holos mainok.
english: The weather is very cold, so wear more clothes.

bnn: Na so'zaq onisin, Asa nito sipongol madas talolong.
english: It's going to rain heavily, you have to remember to bring an umbrella.

bnn: Bitvaqan sa-ngan. Na qodanan onisin maa.
english: There was thunder just now, and it's supposed to rain later.
It just rained, and now it's stopped.
It seems to have rained and the road is wet.

bnn: Qodanan? Mavia as lovos a hobong?
english: Is it raining? Why are you all wet?

bnn: Qodanan a nata, Nii ak madas i talolong.
english: It's raining outside, so I didn't bring an umbrella.

bnn: Madaing a lovlov, Masakbit a bongo kalilovlov on.
english: The wind is blowing so hard that my head hurts.

bnn: Madaing a vali, Qalipasav a bongo asvali on.
english: The sun is so big, it makes me dizzy.
I forgot to bring my pen.
I forgot to bring my chopsticks.

bnn: Nii aak amin madas, Mabaliv ata.
english: I don't have one either, let's go buy one.
Let's go buy a pen, shall we?
Well, I still have to buy erasers.
Let's go get breakfast, shall we?

bnn: Nii aak, Minaon in aak han lomaq.
english: No, I've already eaten at home.
I forgot to steam my lunchbox.
I forgot to bring my lunchbox.
Then let's eat my lunch box together!
What are you having for lunch?

bnn: Na maon aak isia kako pisihal hobong to paitotaongqo.
english: I want a nutritious school lunch.
What are you having for lunch?

bnn: Haiza nak haip dason timoqos, Moskon ata taongqo in maon.
english: I've brought a lunchbox today, let's eat together at noon!
Let's go play basketball, shall we?
