english: Great! It is a bumper crop today with full fish baskets.

bnn: Mahiav ata mocoqais namoskon ata paqosil.
english: Let's go back immediately and share it with everyone.

bnn: Aka'avin to kavivila, mocoqaisa ha'an pangka'olongqo' an so'o.
english: Stop playing and quickly sit in your seat.

bnn: Malkahima' ca haip, namol'oo ca laqbing, moskon ata modan kavila ti.
english: It's Friday today, we have a day off tomorrow. Let's go out and play together!

bnn: Macial na, moskon ata monvaqlac ti.
english: Great! Let's go to the riverside.
What day will it be tomorrow?

bnn: Malkati'on ca laqbing, moskon ata laqbing qani'an kavila' mali' qa.
english: Tomorrow will be Wednesday. Let's go play ball tomorrow afternoon!
What will you be doing tomorrow morning?

bnn: Ulo'an ca laqbing, namoskon azak tina nak monsomsoman.
english: Tomorrow will be Sunday, I will be going to church with my mom.

bnn: Asa cak motaq, namodan cak kilim i 'otaki'an.
english: I feel like vomiting. I need to go to the restroom.

bnn: Tataqo, macakbit ca tian nak, asa kilim 'otaki'an.
english: Teacher, I have a stomachache. I need to go to the restroom.
May I go wash my hands?
It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.

bnn: Tataqo, macakbit sala ca bongo, namoloo cak ca qani'anin.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.
Okay, take care and go home.

bnn: Tataqo, namoloo cak ca moqnin malkac'an. maopa'i nasadoo cak ising.
english: Teacher, I need to take a sick leave next Monday. I have to see a doctor.

bnn: Han cia 'otaki'an, macakbit dao ca tian cia.
english: She has a stomachache. She's in the restroom.

bnn: Tataqo, macakbit ca qongqongan it Malan, moloo cia haip
english: Teacher, Malan has a sore throat. She took a sick leave today.

bnn: Makoa cona oka' at Kaot maipati?
Bazai Tamalasan cak, macanin qamisan nak haip.
english: My name is Bazai Tamalasan, and I'm 10 years old.
Are all your family members indigenous?

bnn: Uo, mo'amin ca tatlomaq nam bonon coko.
english: Yes, my whole family is Bunun.

bnn: Nii, Bonon coko' at Tama nak, boot ca tina nak.
english: No, my father is Bunun, and my mother is Han Taiwanese.

bnn: Tama soo ca mazka'i? piin qamisan cia?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

bnn: Nii, madadaingaz i acang nam at konan, mavao'onin ca qamisan cia.
english: No, he is an elder of our tribe. He is 80 years old.

bnn: Mac'an qan vao'in ca qamisan it toqasnanaz nak.
Madaing sala ca qamisan it toqasnanaz maka' so'o?
english: Is your brother much older than you?

bnn: Tatsaba anian qan masipaton taknol ca kidaqvasan nak.
Talmontokin nito pasado, mindaqvasin aso ki qa?
english: I haven't seen you in a while. Have you grown taller?

bnn: Uo, tatsaba anian qan mati'onin taknol ca kidaqvasan nak.
Namaipa caak kokozaon tataqo kilim i tataqo.
english: I'm going to the office to see the teacher.
He's going to throw away the trash.

bnn: Ihan cia ki tonhapavan, napalontan at cia onin tonhahapav.
english: He's at the swimming pool. He's going to compete in a swimming competition later.

bnn: Icaqat Kaot a? napalontan a cia onin i malilia qai.
english: Where is Kaut? She's going to compete in a running competition later.

bnn: Iha'an cia o'inonan i masisipol a, loklacon zako ti.
english: She's in the auditorium. I'll go call her.
Let's go to the playground together.

bnn: Mongaosang azak mabaliv i paitototosvali, kilimon zako aso ca onin.
english: I'll go buy lunch first, and then I'll meet you later.

bnn: Moskon ata ancaqan i maoqos qa!
english: Let's carry the lunch boxes together!

bnn: Kilimang noma', maopa'i nakilim ca ki tataqo.
english: You find someone else, I'm going to find the teacher.

bnn: Palontan at Bato kit matoqtoqmali' haip?
english: Is Batu competing in croquet today?

bnn: Nii, napalontan a cia ki tidangkolan.
english: No, he's competing in high jump.

bnn: Naminhamo aso ki palontan ca todiipin han palontanan?
english: Will you compete in the sports day?

bnn: Namakama'az ata ca todiipin han palontanan?
english: What will we do in the sports day?
We will compete in tug of war.
Will we sell food at the sports day?

bnn: Lavai qana aso dia, mamanano' qana!
english: Congratulations on getting first place! You're amazing!

bnn: Uo haiza, han cia sapalan masabaq.
english: Yes, she's sleeping in her room.

bnn: Uka', laopang a cia modata', nasanavanin cia mocoqais.
english: No, she's not. She just went out and will be back in the evening.

bnn: Han cia dosa'laoto, mondaza'a aso kilim cia ti.
english: He's upstairs. You can go up and find him.

bnn: Uo Bazai qana, talbontoking nito pasadoo, macial aso?
english: It's Bazai. I haven't seen you in a while! How have you been?

bnn: Macial na! maipati caak kilim so'on pababazbaz.
english: I'm doing great! I came to chat with you.

bnn: Iha'an cia pitdai'an makal'ing i sanglav, loklacan zako.
english: He's in the kitchen cooking. Let me go call him.

bnn: Maipa cia tolkokan madamo kis tolkok.
english: She went to the chicken coop to catch chickens.

bnn: Uka' qodasnanaz moo han lomaq, iha'an cia qoma, hanamo lomaq mantatala cia mocoqais.
english: Your grandfather is not at home. He's in the field. Wait for him to come back.

bnn: Talmontoking nito pasadoo, taldaqvasing aso ki.
english: I haven't seen you in a while. You've grown taller.
It's so good to see you.

bnn: paimoo ca onglai dii, pokombo'is piskazhavan.
english: Here's a pineapple for you. Put it in the refrigerator.

bnn: talmontoking nito' pasadoo, loklaconko nai moskon maon qaising ti.
english: It's been a while. Let's have a meal together.

bnn: Bazing nii, maqto'ing ca qo'in savil, maipa ata polongqo'an pababazbaz ti.
english: No need to bother. I'll just have tea. Let's sit in the living room and chat.

bnn: Miqomicang iso to malkacia tantongoan, namodanin caak.
english: Thank you for your hospitality. I have to go now.

bnn: Laopang ca tolkok dii sintono, dasi nadaokdaokon soo ma'on.
english: This chicken was just freshly killed. Take it home and enjoy it slowly.

bnn: Maqto ata patataqo' ca laqbing mina'onin?
english: Can I make an appointment with you tomorrow afternoon?

bnn: Han ata sipolan pasadoo ti? nasiza'an ata qaningo.
english: How about meeting at school? We need to shoot a video.

bnn: Maipa ata olo'nonan ti? napainok caak i holocbonon maipata.
english: Then let's go to the community center. I'll wear folk costume.

bnn: Manao'az hala qai dandan han acang nam, kilimi caak ca kapoaqin.
english: The cherry blossoms in our tribe are beautiful when they bloom. Come find me when the flowers bloom!

bnn: Namaltatalavang pancan nangqatqanin ca, madia'ang qanin antala'an pa!
english: That would have to wait until spring. It's too late, isn't it?
Then come during our Thanksgiving Festival!
Alright! I'm looking forward to it!

bnn: Makoacona ozav aso mocoqais han acang miqomic?
english: May I ask why you decided to move back to the tribe?
I want to return to teach at the local school.

bnn: mazang aso nito han bokzav mintataqo'?
english: Why not teach in the city?

bnn: Maopa'i minasakak acang nak, maqtoang amin patcoqais i acang.
english: Because I miss my hometown and I also want to give back to the tribe.

bnn: Mananano hala aso matinon, cima taqo so'on i?
english: You're very skilled at weaving, who taught you?

bnn: Ciat qodasnao'az naak, mantan a cia mananaon matinon han acang nam.
english: It was my grandmother, she is the most skilled weaver in our tribe.

bnn: Makoacona asa aso pisqanciap i matinon?
english: How did you develop an interest in learning weaving?

bnn: Maopa'i iniqomican nam ca matinon, asato minsaoqaqabas ca iniqomican dii.
english: Weaving is a part of our culture, and I want to ensure its continuity.

bnn: Mantan macial qodan ca davoc dii.
Mantatan aso ki, talmontoon ca mataqbo' dii?
english: You're really talented. Does it take a long time to make?

bnn: Nii', maqto'in ca tat'olo'anin, mongaoson ca dolaz matahon, nacosanin mokon mahilaoq, namaqto'in pokombo'on i kal'ong.
english: No, it only takes about a week. After steaming the sticky rice and white rice, we mix it with yeast powder, and then it can be stored in a jar.

bnn: haiza han dii daqpoot cin calobonon, mo'amin sincoaz i naak qai!
english: I have chili and lokiy, both grown by myself!

bnn: Asaonko ca holoc dii, motpok pia coi?
english: I like this piece of clothing. How much is it?
It's too expensive. Can't you lower the price a bit?

bnn: Nii' na, song hala caak ca maqna'on mavanaq.
english: No, if I lower it further, I'll lose money.

bnn: Uo na! cia tas'a holoctaqdong ca siza'on zako.
english: Alright then, I'll take a black piece of clothing.

bnn: Siza'on zako ca viia cin kalong dii.
english: I want this knife and this pot.

bnn: Motpok dosa' sing, inakanak mako'ima sintas'i, maqto talmonto cokao'on.
english: It's a total of 2000 dollars. I handmade these, and they are guaranteed to last a long time.

bnn: Ciat kaviaz naak taqo zakon to maipa'ati mabaliv, maqto moqnang mavadaq tokoc?
english: I'll introduce my friend to buy. Can you give a further discount?

bnn: Uo na, vadaqon zako tokoc i.
english: Alright! I'll give you a discount.

bnn: Maipa'ang dii qamang sadoo, maiza han dii holoc cin tamohong balivon.
english: Come and take a look! We sell clothes and hats.

bnn: Macingav to pia coi ca holoc dii?
Taao saba qan mahima'on ca ta'a holoc, maca taao ka motpok ta'a sing.
english: One piece of clothing is 350 dollars, three pieces for 1000 dollars.

bnn: Maqto'in ta'a ca balivonko, ci'ai baqlo ca isaiv zakon.
english: I'll just buy one piece, please give me a new one.

bnn: Miqomicang, asa caak mabaliv i qaisingdolaz cin qasomaqav.
english: Hello, I would like to buy sticky rice and braised pork with maqaw pepper.

bnn: oka'in ca qaising, haizang ca tanapang, mabaliv aso?
english: The rice is sold out. I have tana pancakes, would you like to buy them?

bnn: Uo ti, aiving tas'a, namaipati mabaliv qaising ca moqnin.
english: Alright, please give me one. I'll come back next time to buy rice.

bnn: Uo, kadangazonko aso makociat kapa' mabatiqo, motpok mahima'on coi.
english: Okay, I'll pack it in a bag for you. That'll be 50 dollars.

bnn: Tinpito tokii saak haip tonahaan pasnanava'an.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

bnn: Nakitngaa'in mapasnava, mokombo masnanava monhaan pasnanava'an. Topa lalavian to," Mindangkaza! Masomsoma!,"It's time for class
english: the teacher walked into the classroom

bnn: Maaq to maspasnava a, isnava'an saam masnanava malasBonon masisipol.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Bunun language of numbers.

bnn: Makilansan saam masnanava masipol, tosoas i masisipol to sintosaos.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

bnn: Mapinqansiapin saak madia malasBonon to qalinga.
english: I have learned many Bunun languages.

bnn: Daqdaqanin saak monhaan pasnanava'an, losbot mapasnava malasBonon, nabazbaz saak mapatan'a tina.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Bunun language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

bnn: Topa'on inaak tama ngaan to Umas.
Topa'on inaak tina ngaan to Sani.
Haiza inaak toqasnanaz, topa'on naipa to Laong, mas'an qan tas'a qamisan naipa laopako.
english: I have a brother, his name is Laung, he is 11 years old.
We study in the same school.

bnn: Mazima saak siin inaak to toqasnanaz tosasaos.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

bnn: Mazima saak songqaqaol, maaq to pal'oon a, moskon saam tastolomaq songqaqaol.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

bnn: Mazima saak mapasaqaal baqlo to kaviaz, maqto saam toskon tosasaos siin moskon songqaqaol.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.

bnn: Isia saak Bonon sidoq to ovaz'az.

english: There are five people in our family.
There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

bnn: Moskon saak tama tina toqasnanaz siin toqasnao'az.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.
My father is tall and he is a policeman.
My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

bnn: MalasBonon tama ihaan lomaq pabazbaz zami.
english: My father speaks the Bunun language with us at home.

bnn: Mosoqais saam monhaan asang i pal'oonin.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

bnn: Moskon saak inaak to tais'aan madamo aokaok.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.

bnn: Madaidaz saak inaak tastolomaq to tais'aan.
english: I like our family very much.

bnn: taskon saak haip tina monata tantongo.
english: I went out with my mother today.

bnn: Mataisqang a diqanin to qani'anan, nito makazav, nii amin maklang, kamamakazvav a hivhiv.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

bnn: Ihaan saam maso'ismotan mama'on paang, sanvali'on lotbo taisqang, mastaan to manangqat.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

bnn: Masingav saak tina to, mavia diqanin to mindangqasin i?
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

bnn: Topa tina to, lao naminsoma'in balivosan.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

bnn: Uka lohom ihaan diqanin to sanavan, minsoma'in a bintoqan.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

bnn: Ihaan molomaq to inondadanan, masisaopa saak bintoqan tokas'aang.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

bnn: Maqto'ang balivosan nito mon'iti, asa'ang saak monata tantongo.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

bnn: Inaak pasnanava'an qai, ihaan inaam lomaq to dingalan, daqdaqanin saak kanbantas monhaan pasnanava'an, kanbantas amin molomaq.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

bnn: Nii inaam pasnanava'an madaing, nito papia isnanava'an, mapasaqaal amin saam.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

bnn: Modinoon amin isnanava'an ihaan tindangkolan, moskon pismamali, toskon pababazbaz.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

bnn: Moskon amin saam inaam to masnanava pistanaqtaq. Maszang a pasnanava'an tastolomaqan.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

bnn: Daqdaqanin saam ma'a'asik, moskon mapiningzav i pasnava'an.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

bnn: Haiza bonon maqaisqais i vanaas to tidanoman, haiza bonon ma'asik.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

bnn: Asikon zami pasnanava'an to isaq'isaq, mapa'oskon kozakoza, daqdaqanin maningzav amin a pasnanava'an.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.
Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

bnn: Talmadia'in saam nito mapasadoo, matosalpo saak istaa.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

bnn: Maaq to sado'an saak qodas, pakaonan saak soika, paqodan saak savil.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

bnn: Madavos isia qodas sinsoaz to soika, totoza to manamboq kaonon.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

bnn: Madoo amin saak qoo dodas to savil. masihal amin qodan.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

bnn: Maaq to tongqovali, moskon saak qodasnao'az mapit'ia paitotongqovali.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

bnn: Madia isia qodasnao'az sinpit'ia paitotongovali, haiza iskaan, haiza maitolkok, haiza bahat, haizang ciqotciqot.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

bnn: Maaq to mina'onin paitotongqovali ka, monhaan saam pitsanglavan matingos sanglav.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

bnn: Madia isia qodas siniza to hotan tai siin tolkom pinaak, nadason zako molomaq.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

bnn: Mapalavaaz saak intaa, topa to namoqna ata mapasadoo.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

bnn: Haip to qani'anan, dason saam masnanava monhaan sasaipokan takismomoot, ihaan saam hilav maldailaz baliv kipo.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

bnn: Mapising saak ivot, paaqpon nii saak sadoo ivot.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

bnn: Sinadoo'in saak madia to qazam, ihaan aingka lokis daza kosbabai, haiza toqoo ihaan lokis to loak malsasabaq.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

bnn: Haiza ihaan sasaipokan takismomoot kombo zoo, tas'asikis siin lai'iong, nii saak sinadoo maopata to takismomoot. Manahip is'aang to sinadoo'in haip to qani'anan.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

bnn: Siniza'in saak madia to qaningo, ispasadoo inaak to tama tina.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

bnn: Maaki moqnin a, nataskon saak tama tina mon'ita.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

bnn: Haip to ail'oan, taskon saak toqasnao'az monhaan Taito mintivi pantama'on.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

bnn: Misnahaan saam Taihoko tonkisia monhaan Taito.
english: We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

bnn: Tonahaanin Taito, ma'onting pantama'on laihli monhaan pandodo'an laihli antala zami.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

bnn: Nito daqvisan isia pantama'onta to lomaq, mohiav ma'ontaing laihli ka tonadiipin.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

bnn: Haiza ihaan pantama'on to lomaq dingalan madaing patankaonan to bokzavan, taskon saam tonsozainsia monhaan bokzavanta.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

bnn: Ihaan patankaonan to bokzavan, dason saam pantama'on paka'on sidih siin tontas'asikis.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

bnn: Sanavan, moskon saam monhaan Poot to asang ma'on qaising.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

bnn: Madia ihaan Poot to asang laihli, paaqpon tondaza saam otovai mon'ita.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

bnn: Maaq to namodaanin saam a, tangqa'ionin inaam to otovai, mohazin saam tonlaihli mosoqais.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

bnn: Mosoqaisin saam laopako monhaan Taihoko, nito niapon to, lao okilimanin isia pantama'onta to otovai.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

bnn: Maaq to ovaz'azang saak a, takihaan saak Naihompo. Maaq to isnava'anin saak a, molosqo monhaan Holi, takihaanin amin bokzavan miqomis.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Naihumpu. After I started school, we moved to Puli and have been living in the city ever since.

bnn: Maaq to ihaanin saak zaingako isnava'an a, isnava'an saak pali'oni Takisilazan miniqomis to kainqansiapan, maqansiap to, haiza takihaan Taivangti Takisilazan miniqomis madia makitvaivi to iniqomisan.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

bnn: Paaqpo, maaq to pal'oonin a, moskon saak inaak toqasnanaz monhaan asang kilim madadaingaz tantongo, asa pinqansiap anak'anak sidoq iniqomisan to kaitaiklasan.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

bnn: Mavao'onin qamisan a madaingaza, qaito, maszangang talmaidoo'ang sado'an.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

bnn: Singavon zako to piaq isiata qalinga qansiapon? Madaozong naipa malasBonon, maqto amin malasPoot siin malasLipoon pababazbaz.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Bunun, as well as Hokkien and Japanese.

bnn: Maaq to singavonin a, todiipin saak maqansiap to, misnahaan naipa ovaz'azang isnava'an malasLipoon, binanao'az qai Bonon. Maaq to kozakoza naipa qai, mapasaqaal madia to Poot. Paaqpon, madia isiata qansiapon qalinga isbabazbaz.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Bunun, and he knows many Hokkien at work, so he can speak so many languages.

bnn: Maaq to tantongo saam a, madia isia madaingazta isbazbaz pali'oni qanop to kaitiklasan.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

bnn: Anatopa to nii a qalinga aminon zako itqaal tan'a ka, langati makosia saam ima-zingva siza qaningo, namaqto'ang oqna'on ikmantokon tan'a.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

bnn: Nii saak matlaz maqansiap anak'anak iniqomisan to ovavaz'azang, matokaz'av to anak'anak qai Takisilazan to miniqomis.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

bnn: Maaq to madia'in inaak qansiapon a, haiza'in iniliskinan to Bonon saak, makitvaivi to bonon, haiza'an amin maqto iskokoniv to kaitaikladsan.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Bunun is unique and something to be proud of.

bnn: Maaq haip to dalavdav a, namosoqaisin naobahbnanaz molomaq.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

bnn: Moskon saak qodasnao'az monhaan babalivan mabaliv tolkok, mapalsanos mapit'ia manamboq to kakaonon ispaka'on naobahnanaz.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

bnn: Maaq to angqai saam babalivan sanglav a, madia ihaan babalivan laopang siniza to sanglav.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

bnn: mabaliv saam sanglav, bahat siin tao'las-dangqas.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

bnn: Andingalan babalivan kakaonon to bonon topa to," Madavos inaak to bonglai siin qalop, mabaliva to tikis."
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

bnn: Angqai saam babalivan titi, topa Taokii to," Ma'aq isoo nabalivon? Masmoq to madaing a haip to maitolkok, tas'a qai tao sabah soi."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

bnn: Topa qodas to mastaan maqlis, tosingav Taokii to, lao maqto vanaqan to tikis soi.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

bnn: Qaito, topa Taokii to nito maqlis, ni'in maqto vanaqan soi.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

bnn: Topa ka andingalan to Taokii to, mabaliva inaak to iskaan, madaing a iskaan a, nito maqlis.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

bnn: Kinozin a, mabalivin saam maitolkok siin iskaan, mosoqais molomaq mapit'ia tasto pangka to pan'ai'an.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

bnn: Patonpaklis naobahnanaz topa to, mosqa sivitai nito maqto pal'oon, nahaanin moqnin to islongo'an todiip maqto mosoqais.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

bnn: Topa qodasnao'az to, madia a sinpit'ia, loklasi amin tastolomaq to tais'aan koskon ma'on!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

bnn: Tan'ali saam madia to taisis'aan, koskon ma'on manamboq paitosanavan to kakaonon.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

bnn: Haiza inaak tatini o'oskonan topa'on to Tiang, losbot naipa panpopongol madas ikma'ai'on.
english: I have a classmate named Tiang, he often forgets to bring things.

bnn: Maaki isnava'an a, simol naipa o'oskonan ispapatas, isqaqaisqais nait patasan.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

bnn: Mos'an moposan moti'on, todiip saam mapasimol istaa.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

bnn: Qaito, madikla naipa i, losbot simol ikma'ai'on a nito masoqais sinimolan.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

bnn: Kinozin, ni'in amin saam asa mapasimol istaa ikma'ai'on.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

bnn: Haiza to tastodiqanin, moskon saam monhaan bokzavan tantongo.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

bnn: Ihaan inondadanan, asa Tiang monhaan pattaki'an, qaito, panpongol naipa madas isqaqaisqais to haqil.
english: On the way, Tiang wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

bnn: Masaopa naipa o'oskonan simol isqaqaisqais to haqil, qaito, antalam amin saam to, nii amin minadas.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

bnn: Tin'iangiang a Tiang tatangis, masoqnoq naipa topa to, "Mavia amo to nito mapasimol zako isqaqaisqais to haqil i!"
english: Tiang aw burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

bnn: Topa ka o'oskonan istaa to, "Maopa i nii aso ana'anak madas a, mosasoo to, mapasimol saam so'o ikma'ai'on a, nii amin aso masoqais."
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

bnn: Maaq to laqbingin a, matingmot a Tiang monhaan pasnanava'an, soqaison amin sinimol Tiang to ikma'ai'on pisia o'oskonan.
english: The next day at school, Tiang arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

bnn: Matokaz'av Tiang masisaopa o'oskonan bazbaz to, na'anak'in naipa qabasin madas ikma'ai'on. Matomasqing amin naipa o'oskonan to, mitoza qabas mapasimol istaa ikmama'ai'on.
english: Tiang apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.

bnn: Inaak to tama qai, takihaan asang qaqanop to mamangan.
english: My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

bnn: Maaq to ovaz'azang saak ka, moskon tama siin pantama'on sanavan monata, madas i via siin bosol.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

bnn: Maaq to tosqangin diqanin a, madas naingka qinanop to titi mosoqais.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

bnn: Minton sia vanis, minton sia haval, miniton amin haiza linas.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

bnn: Pisihalon intaa ihaan lomaq mapaqosil titi, ispaqoqosil i taisis'aan.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

bnn: Losboq saak topa tama to, asa makilansan tama qanop.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

bnn: Topa tama zako to, maaki taldaingin saak a, todiipin madas zako monlodon.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

bnn: Takihaan asang to maidodoaz, maqansiap amin makosia haqo madamo takismomoot. Matas'i naingka lismosqot siin labantiq to haqo.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

bnn: Maqansiap inaak tama matas'i lismosqot to sinpalasong.Topa tama to, iskosia naipi madamo linas, asa ata to matqas masailang takismomoot to dinapan. Maaq a sinpalasong to haqo qai, asa to pihanon takimomoot nalaqaiban to daan.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

bnn: Tis'oni saak asa mahiav taskon madadaingaz monlodon qaqanop, daqdaqanin saak pinanaam matas'i haqo. Mohiav a, namaqto'in inaak sintas'i to haqo, totoza to odamo'an i takismomoot.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

bnn: Sinadoo'in tama inaak to sintas'i ka, topa naipa zako to, namin'oni saak qabasin mamangan to qaqanop.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

bnn: Laopako, taldaingin saak, mama saak inaak to bosol-kavi siin koos, makilansan tama monhaan lodon qanop.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

bnn: Maaq to mosiqais monhaan asang qai, mapaqosil qinanop to titi pisia taisis'aan.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

bnn: Topa tama to, "Asa ata to matomasqing maimadadaingaz to sintoqomis, mintoza ata oqanopan i madia to sinpapanaq."
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.

bnn: Halasan azak haip to tingmot monhaan pasnanava'an.
english: I was late for school this morning.

bnn: Maaq to tonahaan azak pasnanava'an qai, panpongol azaK madas kavaang.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.

bnn: Nii azak minadas ma'aqma'aq to qaimangsot.
english: I didn't bring anything with me.

bnn: Maaq to isnava'an azak qai, moskon azak o'oskonan sadoo patasan.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

bnn: Maaq to palatanam mapatas qai, pasimolan azak o'oskonan ispapatas siin isqaqaisqais.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

bnn: Topa'on azak masnanava to, "Tingmota moqnin min'anoqo, kaa'in halasan!,"The teacher told me
english: "Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!""

bnn: Inaak kaviaz qai topa'on to Talom, isia amin naipa Bonon sidoq to ovaz'az.
english: My good friend's name is Talum, and he is also an Bunun child.

bnn: Moskon azam ihaan Izokan to asang masisipol patasan.
english: We study together in the Izukan tribe.

bnn: Masiqailis azam moskon tan'a madadaingaz taqo paliqabasan, maqansiap amin azam malasBonon.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Bunun proficiently.

bnn: Malaongkav azak to masmoq amin, manisnis makois a Talom.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Talum is short and thin.

bnn: Matanaqtaq a Talom, mazima amin azam istaa.
english: Talum is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

bnn: Haip qai isia pasnanava'an paintataiv to qani'anan, papia ka inhamo'on to paintataiv.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

bnn: Haiza pasibotbot, kantondaq mali, tindangkol, olozi siin manaq bosol-kavi.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

bnn: Maaq to tindangkol azak a, tiskapat azak, madia ihaan boqtong to qaidang motaol.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.

bnn: Qaito mindangkaz azak, maldaok masaopa tanangaos tindangkol.
english: But I stood up and continued running forward.

bnn: Maaq to tonahaan azak panatpo'an qai, manahip amin a sikaopa to bonon.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

bnn: Ananatopa to nii azak makitngangaos tindangkol, qaito manahip azak, maopa'i pankanaqtongin azak paintataiv.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

bnn: Taskon azak takna tama monhaan inaak to pantama'on tantongo.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

bnn: Topa'on azam istaa to, haiza ihaan tavi moboat to loak.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

bnn: Maaq to minkangna naipa tavi qai, misnahaan tavi motingkol pananasto.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

bnn: Madas tama ki maiqanvang to titi siin saviki isaiv inaak to pantama'on.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

bnn: Moskon azak pantama'on ihaan sapalan pababazbaz, taqo naipa madia paliqabasan to sintataqo.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

bnn: Maaq to namodaanin azak qai, tomasqingon azak pantama'on to malaongkavin, talmaindoo'in amin sado'an.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

bnn: Topa azak to, "Maaki mindadoo'in pantama'on to bantas a, monhaana amin inaam to lomaq tantongo ki moqnin."
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

bnn: Ihaan 2022 to painsanan, tis'oni Seho maqto ihaan Mivonsio sinpatas to ngaan "pantas'aon malasBonon to ngaan mapatas" to sinkozakoza mo'ampok mapaliqansiap.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

bnn: Mintivi azak malibonto'in masisaopa Seho makas'aang to, maqto a ihaan Mivonsio sinpatas to ngaan "pantas'aon malasBonon to ngaan mapatas" sinkozakoza to maindodo'az Taopa Soqloman.
english: I interviewed Taupas Suqluman, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

bnn: Mapatopa'in azam to na'ihaan haip to islongqo'an to diqanin monhaan isiata to lomaq mintivi istaa.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

bnn: Maaq to mintivi azak istaa qai, masisaopa naipa zako mapinqansiap isiata sinpatingaan to kanada'an, madas amin zako mapasaqaal isiata to tastolomaqan, isiata al'asangan to asang.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

bnn: Tosingavon zako naipa to, mavia to malmanano sisasaa topa to, asa sinpatas ngaan to inkangna'an mapatas, nii qo qabas sinpatas to ngaan masihal?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

bnn: Topa Taopas Soqloman to, "Maaq a sinpatas malasBonon to ngaan qai, siata nano inaam mamantok to ngaan. Maaq inaak to ngaan qai mapitqas inaam to tastosidoqan, inaam to tastolomaqan, taki'isaq azam to miniqomis, maqto'ang malalabas to taisis'aan maqto sisoqais anak'anak to ngaan."
english: Taupas Suqluman said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

bnn: Moskon azak qodasnao'az takna monhaan babalivan mapabaliv sanglav, madas a qodasnao'az madia kain'anakan masoaz to sanglav, matas'i amin madia manamboq to kakaonon ispaka'on taisis'aan.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

bnn: Mazima amin taisis'aan isia qodasnao'az to babalivan, madia bonon mabaliv daoqpoot siin pa'isaz tikis, madia bonon tanam ma'on isiata sinpit'ia mahansom to pan'ai'an.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

bnn: Isiata sinhanat to li'li' siin sinpit'ia to madoq qaising qai mastaan to manamboq kaonon, haizang makosia qaimos sinhanat maivanis to titi, madia taisis'aan tis'oni kaihansoman minsoma, ihaan amin inaam babalivan to tanangaos maldailaz.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

bnn: Maaq to mahanat a qodasnao'az qai, ihaan azak dingalan malhano ki minisoma to taisis'aan, ihaan azak dingalan tosqit loloklas topa to, "Kain'anakan zami ka sanglavon sinsoaz, masihal a sintal'ia, kavavaa'a mon'iti mabaliv!"
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

bnn: Mahaipi inaam isbaliv to sanglav pit'aminon mabaliv, topa qodasnao'az to, "Tis'oni amin haiza isoo to sin'indangaz."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

bnn: Maaq a sinkozakozakon qai, mapinqansiapin zako pali'oni Takisilazan miniqomis to sinsosoaz siin kakaonon to kaiqansiapan, mosasoo to matlazin maqansiap malkasia babalivan sinkozakoza to iniqdi'an.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

bnn: Sado'an zako qodasnao'az haiza'an malkasia ito qabas Takisilazan miniqomis kakaonon to kaibaqisan is'aang, mastaan azak matonahip matomasqing.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.
I arrived at school at seven today.

bnn: Na isnavaan in, monkombo masnanava, topa taimi'isnanavan to, "mindangkaza! mastaoqtaoq!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

bnn: Pidaingon zami qalinga topa to, "sinsi miqomisang!"
Isnavan aam a, sinsi masnava isisipol i itomalasBonn to qalinga
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Bunun language of numbers.

bnn: Sisisli aam sinsi masipol, tosasaos aam isisipol to sintosasaos.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

bnn: Mapasnava aak madia to itomalasBonon to qalinga.
english: I have learned many Bunun languages.

bnn: Qanglas aak monKako, qanglas aak mapasnava malasBonon qalinga, na bazbaz aak patan'a ki Tina.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Bunun language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

bnn: Maa naak Tama ngan a topaon to Sipal.
Maa naak Tina ngan a topan to Mai'ia.
Haiza naak tas'a masitoqas-nanaz topaon ngan to Vilian, mas'an qan tas'a istaa qamisan
english: I have a brother, his name is Vilian, he is 11 years old.

bnn: Moskon aam ihaan tas'a kako vingkio.
english: We study in the same school.

bnn: Ma aak siin masitoqas-nanaz naak a mazima aam tosasaos.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

bnn: Mazima aak ton'apap, maqi pal'on a, amin aam tastolomaq moskon ton'apap.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

bnn: Mazima aak mapasaqal baqlo kaviaz, maqto aam moskon tosasaos siin ton'apap.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.
There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

bnn: Moskon aak Tama, Tina, masitoqas-nanaz siin masitoqas-nao'az katoskon aam.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

bnn: Inaak Tama malaongkav, Sasbinaz naak Tama ka.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

bnn: Innak Tina makois, Ising naak Tina ka.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

bnn: Maaq Tama ihaan lomaq a malasBnon pabazbaz zami.
english: My father speaks the Bunun language with us at home.

bnn: Maqei pal'on aam a mosoqais aam mon asang.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

bnn: Moskon aak inaak masitoqas-nanaz masitoqas-nao'az madamo aok'aok.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.

bnn: Mazima aak inaak tastolomaq to Bonon.
english: I like our family very much.

bnn: Haip qanian dosa aak Tina monata qaitmal.
english: I went out with my mother today.

bnn: Qanian to diqanin masanglav saa, nii to makazhav nii amin mabaqais, makahav a lovlov.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

bnn: Ihaan aam nasto ismoot mamaon i anpang, sanvalion valih a hobong, manangqat saa.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

bnn: Topaok Tina to, mavia ka diqanin madangqas.
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

bnn: Topa Tina to, na laoq nalovlovan.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

bnn: Sanavan diqanin oka lohom, santasal in bintoqan.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

bnn: Ihaan na molomaq to daan, taqoan zako a bintoqan inaak to aikas'angan.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

bnn: Doo maqto lovlovan nii to minsoma, asang aak monata qaitmal.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

bnn: Ma naak Kako a ihaan inaak lomaq di'ngalan, qanglas aak tan'anak monKako, tan'anak amin mosoqais lomaq.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

bnn: Nii naam Kako madaing, nii amin papia panto, pasasaqal amin.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

bnn: Kaopa ka panto mo'anpok haan daisiqdaing, moskon aam qaitmal mali, moskon pababazbaz.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

bnn: Maqa Sinsi a moskon amin zami qaitmal, maqa Kako a maszang tastolomaq.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

bnn: Maisiqailis aam ma'asik, mintos aam piningzav inaam pasnanavan to da'ngianan.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

bnn: Haiza a maqaiqais vanas, haiza a ma'asik.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

bnn: Ma'asikang aam amin Kako to sikaopa tansiki'an, mintos kaskon kozakoza, maqa Kako a na malniningzavin.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

bnn: Takna, monhaan aak asang tantongo haan Aki.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

bnn: Talmadiin aam nii to mapasado, minliliskin aak istaa.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

bnn: Sado a Aki zako, pakaon zako ki sikoa, paqoo zako ocia.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

bnn: Sinsoaz Aki to sikoa madavosdaingaz, totoza to masihal saa kaonon.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

bnn: Mazima aak amin Aki to ocia, masihal amin qoodan.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

bnn: Isaan tinaongqo, dosa aak Bai mapit'ia paitotaongqo.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

bnn: Mapit'ia ka Bai madia to paitotaongqo, haiza iskaan, haiza maitolkok, haiza bahat, haiza ang siqot.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

bnn: Minaon in paitotaongqo, monhaan aam patsanglavan mati'ngos sanglav.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

bnn: Siza Bai madia to hotan, tai siin salo-pinasaq masaiv zako, nadason dao zako polomaq.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

bnn: Tokakivok aingka, topaok to namoqna mapasadoo intaa.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

bnn: Haip qanian dason aam Sinsi monhaan patsinanaipokan, ihaan aam hilav pandailaz namabaliv i kipo.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

bnn: Monkombo in aam haan patsinanaipokan a, topa Sinsi to, "maqa malngos a tastoloqei, maqa tanhiko a tasto'ivot anaka amo sadoo."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

bnn: Mapising aak ivot, paqpon nii aak sadoo ivot.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

bnn: Saido in aak madia loqei, isaan aingka lokis kosbabai, haiz'ang sadoo ki bitqoh ihaan loak lokis masabaq.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

bnn: Patsinanaipokan kombo haiza zao, oma, laoho, mainaqabas nii ang saidoo sinanaipok ton, saidoo in haip manano manaskal saa.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

bnn: Madia naak sinpaisasing, na pasadoo zako Tama Tina.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

bnn: Maqei moqnin na moskon aak Tama Tina masaopa tii.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

bnn: Ma haip pal'on qanian, dosa aak masitoqas-nao'az monhaan Taito' tantongo haan pantamaon ta.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

bnn: Maina haan aam Taihoko tonlaihlai monhaan Taito'.
english: We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

bnn: Panhaan in Taito' a, pantamaon ma'onting laihlaih monhaan papando'an antala zami.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

bnn: Papando'an i pantamaon ta lomaq nii to pakadaqvis, maon'ting mohiav a pandipin.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

bnn: Pantamaon lomaq dingalan haiza madaing to sasaipokan sinanaipok, moskon aam tontaontaon monhaan sasaipokan sinanaipok.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

bnn: Ihaan sasaipokan sinanaipok ta, dason aam pantamaon mapakaon i sidih siin ton'oma.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

bnn: Sanavan, moskon aam mohaan malalabasan dangi'anan ma'on.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

bnn: Madia malalabasan dangi'anan ta laihlaih, paqpon tondaza aam paotpat mon'ita.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

bnn: Namodanin a, sado to tangqai'io'on a paotpaot, losqa in aam tonvaso modaan.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

bnn: Maa laopadao aam mosqais in haan Taihoko, nii niap to okiliman in naopa panTamaon to paotpaot.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

bnn: Atikis ang aak ihaan aam lomaq Baho'an, panto in aak a, tonlosqo in panhaan Taihoko, losbot in haan Tokai miqomis.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Bahu'an. After I started school, we moved to Taipei and have been living in the city ever since.

bnn: Vingkio in Zaingako a, mapasnava aak pali'oni takiSilazan vongka to ispasnanava, mingqansiapin to haizan vaivivaivi to vongka.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

bnn: Paqpon, haip posana talaban pal'oon, dosa aam inaak masitoqas-nanaz mosoqis asang tantongo haan madadaingaz, na asa minqansiap anakanak sidoq to vongka.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

bnn: Madaingaz haizin to mavaon qamisan, qaal sadoan maszangang talotbo to Bonon.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

bnn: Masi'ngav aak istaa to maaq soo qansaipon qalinga, isia taa sinpalasBonon madaozong, maqansiap amin malasBantalang, malasNgaingai, malasPoot.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Bunun, as well as Pangcah, Hakka and Hokkien.

bnn: Masingav istaa minqansiap in to, paqan i ovaz'az ang aipa mapasnava in malasBantalang, Ngaingai istaa binanao'az, qaal ihaan isiata kozkozaon saqal i Poot, paqpon maqansiap aipa madia vaivivaivi to qalinga.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Pangcah when he was a child, his wife is an Hakka, and he knows many Hokkien at work, so he can speak so many languages.

bnn: Maaq aam mapabazbaz a, maqa madaingaz a pali'oni madia ito qabasan qanop to kaitaiklasan.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

bnn: Qaal nii aam maqto ma'laz itqaal tan'a, qaal kosia aam soci sizaan qalinga, na maqto oqnaon ikmantok tan'a.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

bnn: Uvaz'az ang aak nii ang oqansaipan anakanak sidoq to vongka, malka anakanak to takiSilazan a maz'av saa.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

bnn: Madia in ingqansaipon a, dongzav in minqansiap to Bonon sidoq aak, toza to makitvaivi, manano to maqto na iskokoniv.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Bunun is unique and something to be proud of.

bnn: Haip qanian to minsanavan, masinaoba-nanaz na molomaqin.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

bnn: zako siin bai monhaan babalivan tolkok, palhanos mapit'ia paitosanavan na pakaon i masinaoba-nanaz.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

bnn: Angqai aam babalivan sanglav, ihaan babalivan-sanglav haiza madia baqlo siniza to sanglav.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

bnn: Mabaliv aam sanglav-kabo, tanbona siin ningzing.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

bnn: Di'ngalan Taimibabalivan qoqot'aqon to Bonon topato, "ma naak bonglai siin qalop madavos. Mabaliva to tikis maa!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

bnn: Mabaliv in aam bonglai siin qalop.
Angqai aam babalivan titi', topa Taimibabalivan to, "maaq soo nabalivon? maaq haip a tolkok madaing to ma'avola, tas'a ka tao saba soi."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

bnn: Bai tinliskin to maqlis saa, masingav i Taimibabalivan to doo maqto nii to piqlison.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

bnn: Qaal topa ka Taimibabalivan to nano in to nii to maqlis, niin maqto vanaqan maa.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

bnn: Dingalan to Taimibabalivan topa to zain mabaliv inaak iskaan, inaak iskaan madaing to nii to maqlis.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

bnn: Kinoz in mabaliv aam tolkok mabaliv amin iskaan, kalomaqin in mapit'ia ki tasto'sokoi to sanglav.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.

bnn: Talmadia mantala, tinmaqmot in a diqanin.
english: After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

bnn: Masinaoba-nanaz kazingva mosoqis taqo, taisangdangian tisqa nii to maqto pal'on, na moqnin to lihai minsoma.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

bnn: Topa ka Bai to haizin madia a pinit'ia, amin i loklas to zain ma'on!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

bnn: Tan'ali aam kaopa tais'aan, moskon a ma'on madia sinpit'ia to paitosanavan.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

bnn: Haiza naak o'oskonan vingkio topaon to Lomav, qanglas aipa panpongol madas qaimangsot.
english: I have a classmate named Lumav, he often forgets to bring things.

bnn: Maqi isnavan a, simol aipa isia ta o'oskonan vingkio to ispapatas, isqaqaiqais maqi nii a papatasan.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

bnn: Motas'a, modosa, motao, amin pasimol istaa qaimangsot.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

bnn: Qaal haiza istaa madikla to sinkozakoza, qanglas simol a nii to masoqis.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

bnn: Kinozin a amin as'nii mapasimol istaa.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

bnn: Haiza to tas'a qanian, moskon aam monata modandan qaitmal.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

bnn: Ihaan daan, asa Lomav monhaan onanataan, qaal panpongol madas isqaqaiso.
english: On the way, Lumav wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

bnn: Simol aipa haan o'oskonan vingkio i isqaqaiso, qaal amin antalam to, nii aak amin saimadas.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

bnn: Lomav minkaivakaiva santangis. Mahao aipa topa to, mavia amoo nii to pasimol i isqaqaiso!
english: Lumav burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

bnn: U'oskonan vingkio taqo istaa, aopa nii aas anak madas, amin to pasimol soo to qaimangsot, nii to masoqis!
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

bnn: Laqbingin monKako, Lomav tingmot ang monKako in, Lomav boton istaa sinimolan o'oskonan to qaimangsot soqaison in istaa.
english: The next day at school, Lumav arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

bnn: Lomav mansomanai i o'oskonan ta, mosaso topa to na anak in madas qaimangsot, man oninang o'oskonan vingkio maqto haihaip ti mapasimol qaimangsot.
english: Lumav apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.

bnn: Inaak Tama sia asang qaqanop to Bonon.
english: My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

bnn: Maaq aak atikis ang a, Tama siin Pantamaon ihaan sanavan modaan, madas i via siin bosol.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

bnn: Tintosqangngin a, madas aingka qainanop to titi' mosoqis.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

bnn: Minton sia vanis, minton sia haval, doandoan haiza amin linas
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

bnn: 6. Isan aingka asang ngaos daan pisihalon mapaqosil qainanopan, maqosil i asang to Bonon.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

bnn: Qailis aak bonto topaki Tama, na sanlavi ki Tama qanop.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

bnn: Topa ka Tama to na todip i taldaingin aas na todip aipa madas zako.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

bnn: Asang to banananaz kosia amin haqo madamo taklilibos, matas'i aingka haqo-mosqot siin haqo-bato.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

bnn: Inaak Tama maqansiap saa matas'i haqo-mosqot, topa Tama to, maaq aipi a is'patishaqo ki linas, asa ata to masailang napatishaqon to dapan, haqo pisanon angqaqaiban na patishaqon to daan.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

bnn: Tis'onin na maqto kava makilavi madadaingaz moskon qanop, mai'siqalis qanian tanam aak matas'i ki haqo, dongzavin inaak to haqo maqto in otishaqoan.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

bnn: Sadon a Tama ka malkazako topa to na ma dao aak qabasin a nii to kantang to qaqanop Bonon.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

bnn: Lapadao taldaingngin aak, mama' aak inaak to bosolkaka siin koos, kinozkinoz i Tama moskon qanop.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

bnn: Mosoqis in asang boton sinqainanop to titi' isngono ki tasto asang Bonon.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

bnn: Topa ka Tama to, asa to matomasqing tamadaza to sintoqomis, na maqto ata oqanopan madia to qainanop.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.
I was late for school this morning.

bnn: Ma'almonkako a, panpongol aak madas i kavaang.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

bnn: Maqei isnavan a, moskon aak o'oskonan sado haqil.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

bnn: Maqei siking a, o'oskonan pasimol zako inpico siin isqaqaisqais.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

bnn: Topa sinsi zako "Maqei moqnin asa tingmotang minnoqo, asa nii'in to halasan!"
english: The teacher told me, Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!""

bnn: Inaak kaviaz topaon to Sipal, Bonon sidoq aipa amin.
english: My good friend's name is Sipal, and he is also an Bunun child.

bnn: Moskon aam ihaan Bahoan asang vingkio.
english: We study together in the Bahuan tribe.

bnn: Qanglas aam moskon tan'a madadaingaz paliqabasan, maqansiap aam malasBonon.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Bunun proficiently.

bnn: Madaqvas aak amin to maqolpiq, ma Sipal a mapotis to makois.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Sipal is short and thin.

bnn: Matamasaz a Sipal, amin mazima istaa.
english: Sipal is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

bnn: Haip qanian isia Kako to onzokai, kako kozakoza ki madia to ispaintavtaiv.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

bnn: Haiza pasibotbot, pakantondaq mali', Mapasinap, iongi, manaq manaqbosolkavil.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

bnn: Maqi tindakol aak a, motingkol aak, madia pisqaidang haan qaa.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.

bnn: qaal mindangkaz aak, maldaok masinipa ngaos tindangkol.
english: But I stood up and continued running forward.

bnn: Panhaanin aak pas'opa'an amin a bonon manahip.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

bnn: anatopa niito osizaan titas'a ngan, qaal manaskal aak, aopa saokanaqtongin aak paintaivtaiv.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

bnn: takna dosa aamTama tantongo monhaan patamaon.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

bnn: taqo aipa zami, lomaq to tavi moboat tas'a to loak.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

bnn: matas'i aipa tavi ka, maina tavi moqalqal pan'nasto.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

bnn: madas tama ka maiqanvangtiti siin saviki masaiv i pantamaon.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

bnn: dosa aam pantamaon ihaan sapalan pababazbaz, mangono aipa taqo madia to paliqabasan.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

bnn: na modaan tanangaos, patamaon tosqeing zako to taldaqvasin, mintalmaindo'in.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

bnn: topa aak to, mantala pantamaon i minsihalin bantas, moqnin minsoma haan lomaq naam qaitmal.
english: I said, When your foot gets better

bnn: ihaan dosa-singing to maposan qan dosa qamisan, siho tao'aniv Pali'oni takiSilazan mivonsio maqto pintas'aon sidoq ngan to paliqansiap.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

bnn: mintivi masingav i malbonto malka siho taidangazsiza mivonsio, paltas'aon madailaz a sidoq ngan, to asang maindodoaz Sipal.
english: I interviewed Sipal, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

bnn: paitopa'in aam ihaan haip pal'oon to diqanin monhaan isiataa lomaq masingav istaa.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

bnn: ihaan tantongo to aingqaiban, malka zako aipa taqo maimaqoaq isiataa to ngan, dason aak mapasaqal isiataa to tastolomaq, isiataa asang.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

bnn: masingav aak istaa mavia masaa to asa hovaivan a ngan, tato'on to sinpatoki patasan nii to masihal?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

bnn: malka zako aipa topa, aopa makomalasTaloo mapatas nii maqto mamantok taqo ki isiataa to ngan, doma bonon maldaokang loklas i siata to "si'sien'sen," paqpon minhaiza pinqainanon i bonon.
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him \Xi Xian Sheng

bnn: topa Sipal to, takiSilazan qalinga ispapatas to ngan sia imita mamantok to ngan. Inaak to ngan min'oni inaam to sidoq, inaam to tastoqabo, inaam to hobongsinpangqal, maqto'ang haiza madia sidoq tais'aan okiliman sisoqaison to ngan.
english: Sipal said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

bnn: dosa aak takna inaak bai monhaan o'a'anpokan maponhapav babalivan, madas a bai madia kai'anaakan sinsoaz to sanglav, matas'i amin itotakiSilazan kaononkaonon isaiv i bonon.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

bnn: amin mazima isia bai to babalivan, madia bonon mabaliv i daboot siin pa'is, madia amin patanamon ma'on isiataa sihanat isqool.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

bnn: sinhanat to palaqo siin hakhak manano masihal kaonon, haizang makosia maivanis laas mahanat qaimos somalan titi', hivhiv sakon madia a bonon silansanon, amin ihaan inaam to babalivan kanadailaz.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

bnn: ma'almahanat bai kakaonon a, ihaan aak dingalan tao'aniv i bonon. Idingalan aak ma'isqit loklas to, "Sanglav amin kai'anakan masoaz, tail'anaak tal'ia, kavaa mabali maa!"
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

bnn: inaam to kanonkaonon mahiav aminonin isbaliv, topa bai to, "Aopa amin mo'o ka mindangaz! "
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

bnn: maqa kozkozaon a, oqansaipan aak pali'oni takiSilazan to ismomoot siin kakaonon to kaiqansaipan, amin to aingqai'in malkamababaliv to kaisaingo'an.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

bnn: sadoo i bai malka'itoqabasan kakaonon to kaizima'an, maopat aak mastaan makoniv to matomasqing.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.

bnn: aip to cinpito, kosian a saikin pasnanavaan.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

bnn: na'isnavaanin, kosianin a masnanava sian pasnanavaan, at toshit a lavian to, "mindoldola! pissaok!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

bnn: masa isnavaanin hai, isnavaan a kaimin mas malisBonon to issisipol.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the ethnic language of numbers.

bnn: tososolot a kaimin mas masnanavacia masipol, at kahozas a kaimin mas hozassipol.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

bnn: ohansiapan a saikin mas sopah itoBonon to halinga.
english: I have learned many ethnic languages.

bnn: kaopahanian a saikin kosian mas pasnanavaan.
english: I go to school every day

bnn: kaopahanian a saikin mapasnava mas malisBonon.
english: I learn the ethnic language every day
and I want to tell my mother.

bnn: inaak to tama ngaan hai Biong.
inaak to cina ngaan hai Savi.
aizaan a saikin mas tasa to tohasnanaz, topaon a saia to Tahai, aip hai pon11 to hamisan.
english: I have a brother, his name is Tahai, he is 11 years old.

bnn: moskon kaimin isian tasa to pasnanavaan isnavaan.
english: We study in the same school.

bnn: mazima saikin siin inaak to tohasnanaz kahozas.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

bnn: mazima saikin songhaol, mais islongho hai, moskon a kaimin tastolomah kodiip songhaol.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

bnn: mazima saikin mapasahaal mas bahlo to kaviaz, mahto kaimin moskon kahozas siin songhaol.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.

bnn: aizaan inaak tastolomah to tatao ovaaz.
english: There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

bnn: moskon a saikin mas tama cina siin tohasnanaz tohaspingaz minhomis.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

bnn: malaoskav a inaak tama, saia hai kisaco.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

bnn: matokolaaz a inaak cina, saia hai ising.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

bnn: palisBononon a kaimin mas inaak to tama mais ilomah.
english: My father speaks the Bunun language with us at home.
We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

bnn: taskon a saikin mas masitohas madamo takola.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.

bnn: madaidaz a saikin mas inaak to tastolomah.
english: I like our family very much.

bnn: taskon a saikin aip mas inaak to cina kodiip mapahainan.
english: I went out with my mother today.

bnn: masanglav a dihanin mais hanian, nito maklang, nito mabahis, makazavkazav a iv'iv.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

bnn: isian a kaimin maso'ismoot maon mas paang, mais sanvalion hai masmoav to mananghat.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

bnn: masingav saikin mas cina to: mavia to sambaiv a dihaninan i?
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.
Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

bnn: oka a loom masa sanavan, at sandimaldimal a bintohan.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

bnn: masa isian daan, masi'aopa saikin mas bintohan masomsom.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

bnn: mahtoang a balivosa nito minsoma, aopa na'asa'ang saikin mohna kodiip mapahainan.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

bnn: mansisila a inaak pasnanavaan mas inaak to lomah, kaopahanian a saikin kanbantas kosian pasnanavaan, at kanbantas amin kolomah.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

bnn: nii a inaam pasnanavaan madaing, kakaoman a panto, paha mapasahaal amin kaimin.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

bnn: mazima amin a panto moskon isian daisah, pismali siin mahalinga.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

bnn: minsaan amin a masnanava mais moskon mas zamin pishasibang, maszang a pasnanavaan mas tastolomah.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

bnn: kaopahanian a kaimin ma'asik, mapisaningsing mas pasnanavaan.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

bnn: aiza bonon mahaishais mas siol, aiza ma'asik mas boav.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

bnn: ma'asikang kaimin mas iskakaopa to sikvin, maciskon amin kozakoza, paha kaopahanian a inaam pasnanavaan masaningsing.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

bnn: kosian a saikin asang, masa takna tantongo sian inaak to tamahodas.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

bnn: malbontoin a kaimin nito mapasado, paha mililiskin a saikin mas saicia.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

bnn: masa osadoan a tamahodas mas zako hai, mapakaonko mas soika, mapahoodko mas ocia.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

bnn: madavos a itotamahodas sinsoaza soika, toza to masial kaonon.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

bnn: mazima'ik amin mas itotamahodas to ocia, masial amin hoodan.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

bnn: masa taonghovali'in, moskonik mas cinahodas ma'anat mas pinittaonghovali.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

bnn: ma'anat a cinahodas mas vaivivaivi to kakaonon, aiza mai'iskaan, aiza maitolkok, aiza baat, aiza'ang maimomoan
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

bnn: masa minaonin mas pinittaonghovali hai, kosian kaimin pissanglavan kasanglav.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

bnn: siza a cinahodas mas sopah to otan, tai, cilkong, isaiv mas zako to na'ispa'adas kolomah.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

bnn: nasampalavaazin a kaimin at mapatopa to, namohnang tantongo maisinin.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

bnn: aip, adasonim mas masnanava kosian patcician, cindailaz a kaimin sian ilav to namabaliv mas kipo.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

bnn: masa taonangadahin sian patcician hai, topa a masnanava to: maltanangaosan hai hahazam, maltan'ikoa hai i'ivot, kananaka amin sadosado.
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

bnn: aopa mapisingik mas ivot, paha nii a saikin sado mas i'ivot.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

bnn: osadoanik mas sopah to hazam, isian a naia mas lokiscia kosbabai, osadoanangik mas ithoo to isian haitongavlokis masabah.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

bnn: aiza a sisipzoh, loba siin oknav isian patciciancia, nii'ang saikin sinado mas naitaan to cici manaskal i mahto hanian osadoan.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

bnn: macisopah a saikin mas haningo to na'ispasadoko mas tamacina.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

bnn: mais maisinin hai, nataskonik mas tamacina kosaincin.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

bnn: aip to islonghoan, taskonik mas tohaspingaz kosian Taito tantongo sian pantamaon.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.
We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

bnn: masa taonasian Taito, oting a pantamaon mas lailai anpasdo mas zami.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

bnn: aopa mal'aisko a patlailaian mas itopantamaon to lomah, paha ma'aipi mais tonlailai taonadiip.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

bnn: aiza a madaing tatangkaonan mal'aisko mas itopantamaon to lomah, taskon kaimin tontampo kosian tatangkaonancia.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

bnn: isian tatangkaonancia, adason kaimin mas pantamaon mapakaon mas sidi siin tonloba.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

bnn: masa sanavanin, taskonim kosian hici maon mas pinitsanavan.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

bnn: sopahdaingaz a lailai isian hici, paha oting a kaimin mas otobai kodiip.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

bnn: masa namacislodin hai, ishaiapan to tanghaion a otobai, paha kazinim tonbaso.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

bnn: mosohisin a kaimin kosian Taihoko, nito haiap to ado'ingkadoanin a itopantamaon otobai.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

bnn: taikisianik sian Nansalo masa ovaazang haito isnavaanin sian kominkako hai taosian Taihoko, katsianin hici minghomis.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Nansalu. After I started school, we moved to Taipei and have been living in the city ever since.

bnn: isnavaanin sian daikako, mapasnava'ik mas pali'Incomin to ispaspasnava, ohaiapan mas itoTai'oan Incomin vaivivaivi to sinpalihomis.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

bnn: paha, aip to longholabal hai, taskonik mas tohasnanaz kosian mai'asang masingav mas madadaingaz, cis'oni to na'asa ohaiapan mas ito'anak'anak to sinpalihomis.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

bnn: pon80in to hamisan a madaingaza, haito maszangang mas tailotbo mais sadoan.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

bnn: masingavangik saicia to mamaaz a halinga hansiaponso? madaozong a isaicia malisBonon, mahansiap amin malisTa'ialo, malisNGaingai siin malisLipon.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Bunun, as well as Atayal, Hakka and Japanese.

bnn: todiipinik haiap to maipasnava hangsia a saia mas malisLipon masa ovaazang, mosaso Ta'ialo a isaicia pingaz mosaso cis'oni kozakoza at mapasahaal mas sopah to NGaingai, paha haiap sopah to halinga.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Atayal, and he knows many Hakkas at work, so he can speak so many languages.

bnn: masa masingav a kaimin hai, taho a madaingaza mas sopah palihanop to taiklas.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

bnn: haalim nito maplaz to ithaal, haito mako'oni kaimin mas takotaa macihaningo, namahto aipcinin itmantokon.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

bnn: masa ovaazangik hai, nito haiap mas ito'anak'anak to sinpalihomis, paha maz'avmaz'av mais topa to Incomin saikin
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

bnn: mais sopahin haiapon hai, makanadidiip osadoan to min'oni mas Bonon hai makitvaivi, mahto iskoniv.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Bunun is unique and something to be proud of.
My younger brother is going home this evening.

bnn: taskonik mas cinahodas kosian babalivan mabaliv mas tolkok, na'anaton mais sanavanin i na'ispakaon mas naobananaz.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

bnn: anhaibim sian tatansonsanglav, sopah a babahlo sanglav.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

bnn: mabalivim mas takonkon, otanbaona siin taoplasdanghas.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

bnn: malala a mandainglan tatanson mas kanakaonona to, "madavos a inaak bonglai siin halopan. mahto mabaliv to kaoman ha!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

bnn: anhaibim sian tatanson mas maicici, topa a laopaan to: namaaz balivonso? masmohdaingaz a aip tolkok, kaaz tasa ka 300 to soi.
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

bnn: sa'aklis a cinahodas at masingav to adomahto iasoi'onang to kaoman.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

bnn: haito antalam a laopaan to: iasoidaingazin hai, nii'in to mahto pisvanahon.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

bnn: malala a mansisila laopaan to, "mabaliva inaak to iskaan, madaing at iasoi a inaak iskaan."
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

bnn: kinozin, mabalivim mas tolkok siin iskaan, kolomah ma'anat mas tastopangkaka to pandian.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

bnn: patonding'oa a naobananaz to: tosha a koaping to nito mahto islongho, nasinlonghoin to nicio mahto kolomah.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

bnn: topa a cinahodas to, "sopah a sin'anatan at tan'alia mas bonon to minsomaa koskon."
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

bnn: tan'ali'im mas tas'aan siin tonali, koskon mas vaivivaivi to pinitsanavan.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

bnn: aizaanik tasa aloszangan topaon to Daho, mazima lalaktan.
english: I have a classmate named Dahu, he often forgets to bring things.

bnn: mais isnavaan hai, simol sian aloszangan mas ispapatas, ishahaishais siin ahil.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

bnn: mos'an, mopos'an, mocion, mapasimolang amin aloszangan mas saicia.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

bnn: haito, dangian a saia mas makoang to kainaaman, mais sinimol hai nito masohis.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

bnn: kinozin, nii'in amin asa mapasimol mas saicia.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.
One day, we all went on an outing together.

bnn: isianang daan, cin'asa a Dahoa moonata, haito nito minadas mas ahilkoskos.
english: On the way, Dahu wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

bnn: nasimol a saia sian aloszangan mas ahilkoskos, haito topa amin to: nii'ik amin minadas.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

bnn: kaivakaiva a Dahoa at tangis, malsopnoh topa to, "mavia kamo to nito mapasimolko mas ahilkoskos i!"
english: Dahu burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

bnn: tahoan a saia mas aloszangan to: atanao i niias kanak'anak maadas, mosaso mais pasimolanas hai, nito namasohis."
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

bnn: masa kotonin to isnavaan, macinsanos a Dahoa kosian pasnanavaan, sizaon mas dahocia a sinsisimol masohis sian aloszangan.
english: The next day at school, Dahu arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

bnn: masi'aopa a Daho sian aloszangan pisssohdong, at topa to: nakanak'anakik maisinin maadas mas iskokosia, oninang mas aloszangan i maipasisimolko mas haimangsot.
english: Dahu apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.
My dad is a hunter of the tribe.
