bnn: masa ovaazangik, konata a tama siin pantamaon mais sanavan, maadas mas singhaili siin bosol.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

bnn: mais istos'a'in hai, maadas a naia mas hinanop to cici minsoma.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

bnn: minsaan mais vanis, minsaan mais aval, doandoan aiza cikolas.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

bnn: pavazon naicia a cici, is'siahto sian taisis'aan.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

bnn: kaopakaopa'ik oningai mas tama to namalavi mas tama kodiip hanop.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

bnn: topa a tama to, na'adasonik. mais taldaingin.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

bnn: mahansiap amin a taikisian asang mabananaz mako'aho madamo mas cici, mahansiap a naia ka'oni mas ahodoon siin hatop.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

bnn: mahansiap a inaak tama ka'oni mas ahodoon topa a tama to, is'a'aho a sain mas cikolas, asa kata to samantok mas itocici to kaindapanan, asa a ispalasong to posianon nalahaiban mas naicia.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

bnn: cis'oni to na'asa ma'aipi taskon mas madadaingaz hanop, paha kaopahanian a saikin tatanam malka'aho, zaav a inaak sinpal'aho cisdoan mas cici.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

bnn: masa ishaiapan a tama hai, topako to, namin'onias mas talhanopan.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

bnn: aip, taldainginik, cis'ama'ik mas inaak to bosolkavi siin hatnga, malavi mas tama kodiip hanop.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

bnn: masa taonasianin asang hai, is'siahto zami a hinanopan sian taisis'aan.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

bnn: topa a tama to, asata to matomashing mas Dihanin to sintaohomis, masaiv mita mas sopah to hinanopan.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.

bnn: alasan a saikin masa om'om kaosian pasnanavaan.
english: I was late for school this morning.

bnn: masa kaosian pasnanavaan hai, sipongol a saikin ma'adas mas kabaang.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

bnn: masa isnavaan hai, moskon a saikin mas aloszangan sado mas ahil.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

bnn: masa sikiing hai, pasimolanik mas aloszangan mas ispapatas siin ishahaishais.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

bnn: topaonik mas masnanava to "macingmota minkailas mais mohna'in, kakaa'in alasan!"
english: The teacher told me, "Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!"

bnn: topaon a inaak kaviaz to Biong, itoBonon amin a saia to ovaaz.
english: My good friend's name is Biung, and he is also an Bunun child.

bnn: moskon a kaimin sian Nansalo isnavaan.
english: We study together in the Nansalu tribe.

bnn: mabonto a kaimin moskon ta'aza mas madadaingaz palihabasan, mahansiap amin a kaimin malisBonon.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Bunun proficiently.

bnn: malaoskav a saikin aat masmoh, mapocis a Biong aat matokolaaz.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Biung is short and thin.

bnn: mahatba a Biong, mazima amin bonon mas saicia.
english: Biung is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

bnn: aip hai itopasnanavaan to pantataip, sopah a ispasavai sian pasnanavaan.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

bnn: aiza a mapasibotbot, pismalibantas, cisdadaan, pisvakavaka, pisbosolkavi.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

bnn: ciskapat a saikin masa cisdadaan, pishaidang a, malong.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.

bnn: haito, minsalangka a saikin, macingna'ang cisdadaan.
english: But I stood up and continued running forward.

bnn: masa taonasian pas'opaan a saikin hai manaskal amin a bonon.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

bnn: haal nii a saikin atalo mas taismitasa, haito, manaskal a saikin, aopa saokanahtong a saikin mapasavai.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

bnn: taskonik masa takna mas tama, tantongo sian pantamaon.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

bnn: tahoanim mas saicia to mobolah a itolomah tatavi.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

bnn: masa kahna a saia mas tatavi hai maisnatatavi mohalhal.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

bnn: ma'adas a tama mas maitolkok siin bonbon isaiv mas pantamaon.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

bnn: moskonik mas pantamaon mahalinga sian asabahan, taho a saia mas sopah to habasan.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

bnn: masa namacislodim hai atomaslingonik mas pantamaon to tallaoskavin, mintalmaindoo'in amin.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

bnn: topa'ik to mais mindadoin a itopantamaon bantas hai tantongoa amin sian zamian.
english: I said, "When your foot gets better, come to our house next time and visit us."

bnn: mais isian 2022 painsanan hai namas'ampok a Siho mas pali'oni Incomin to nibonsio to nakatasaan a ngaanBonon mapatas
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

bnn: maisingavik mas mabonto pakasia siho, nasiza mas nakatasa ngaanBonon mapatas sian nibonsio to mindodoaz Haisol Palavian.
english: I interviewed Haisul.Palavian, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

bnn: mapatozikaangin a saikin mas saicia to nakaosian isaicia to lomah masingav mas saicia.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

bnn: masa masisingav hai papasahaalonik to maikosna'isa a isaicia ngaan. papasahaalko amin mas isaicia to tastolomah. isaicia to asang.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

bnn: topaonko a saia to: mavia a kaso to na'asa matsohis nganbobon i? masial aopa a tatoona ispatotoki hai?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

bnn: topaonik mas saicia to aopa nii a patasantaoloo'an mahto mathas to mapishaiap mas isaicia to ngaan. aiza a bonon malala mas saicia to Hai tais'aan, aat min'oni mas iskangingiit.
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him \Hai Xian Sheng

bnn: topa a Haisol.Palavian to: maza mako'oni mas malis'Imcomin mapatas to ngaan hai imita mamantok to ngaan. daihio a inaak ngaanan mas imita to sidoh, imita to sinpathaal. hadang madia a tais'aan masohais mas ito'anak'anak to ngaan.
english: Noami Kulas said, "The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group, our family, our identity. I hope more fellow tribespeople can reclaim their own names."

bnn: taskonik masa takna mas hodaspingaz kaodiip matanson, ma'adas a hodaspingaz mas sopah kai'anak'anakan masoaz to sanglav, ka'oni'ang amin mas kakaononBonon isaiv mas tais'aan.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

bnn: mazima amin a tais'aan mas itohodaspingaz tatansonancia, madia a bonon mabaliv mas mahav siin cilkong, madia a bonon minsoma maon mas sin'anat saicia to pandian.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

bnn: masial kaonon a isaicia inanat to li'li siin pinit'ia to haising, aiza'ang ko'onian haimis mapitsimal to maivanis, si'opa mas madia to dodolap, malsaolok amin sian inaam tatansonantan.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

bnn: mais ma'a'anat a hodaspingaz hai isisila a saikin totoshit loklas mas dodolap to, "maza sanglavan hai kai'anak'anakan to sinsoaz, mail'anak, miskava mabaliv."
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

bnn: ma'aipi a inaam istatanson ispako'amin, topa a hodaspingaz to, "cis'oni aopa aiza a kaso maindangaz."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, "It's all thanks to your help."

bnn: pakasian mas andiip iskozakozatan, opasnavaanik mas itoIncomin lisavaz siin kakaonon to hansiap, mosaso o'intao'onian mas matanson to kai'ihdian.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

bnn: sado mas hodaspingaz to mazimadaingaz mas malantangos to kakaonon, masvinik to makoniv siin sibaoszang.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.

bnn: topa'on cia tama nak ngan to Biong.
topa'on cia tina nak ngan to Aping.
heza nak tatinin masitoqas, topa'on to Lokos, mac'an qan tas'a ka qamisan cia haip
english: I have a brother, his name is Lukus, he is 11 years old.

bnn: maszang nam ma kako' dangian masipol.
english: We study in the same school.
Both my brother and I like to sing.

bnn: mado cak taldanav maca pal'o'on na, moskon cam tastolomaq taldanav.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

bnn: asa cak pasaqal kaviaz, maqto cam moskon tosaoc taldanav.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.
There are three brothers and sisters in our family.
I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

bnn: madaqvas sa tama nak, kisaco' a tama nak.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

bnn: makois sa tina nak, ising nga tina nak.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

bnn: malasbonon na tama nam han lomaq bazbaz zami.
english: My father speaks the Bunun language with us at home.
We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

bnn: moskon cak masitoqas nak madamo opop.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.
I like our family very much.

bnn: dosa' cak tina nak monata haip paqaqenan.
english: I went out with my mother today.

bnn: masanglav va diqanin, nito makazhav nito maklang, makazhav va lovlov.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

bnn: ihan cam nasto ismot mama'on pang, sanvali'an na hobong siklangan.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

bnn: macingav cak tina to "makoacona madangqac ca diqanin."
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.
Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

bnn: sanavan oka lohom han diqanin, minsomain na bintoqan.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

bnn: ihan molomaq to dan, topaon zako ka bintoqan to.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

bnn: maqto'ang oka' a lovlov minsoma, opa asang cak moqnang monata paqaqenan.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

bnn: han nak ka kako' ngalan lomaq nam, daqdaqqanin cak tan'anak monhan kako', tan'anak amin molomaq.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

bnn: ni nam ma kako' madaing, nito madia' a panto', amin cam pasaqal.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

bnn: amin na ovava'az si'anpok han deseq, moskon pismali', moskon pababazbaz.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

bnn: moskon amin na sinsi' zami paqaqenan, maszang nga kako' tastolomaq.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

bnn: daqdaqqanin cam ma'asik, asato piningzavon na dangi'an ma'asik.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.
Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

bnn: asikon amin zami ka caikociako ki kako', paqosil cam kokoza, daqdaqqanin na kako' maningzav.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

bnn: monhan cak takna acang tantongo han qodasnanaz.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

bnn: talmadin cam nito pasado, miliskin cak cia.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

bnn: sado ka qodasnanaz zako, oson cak pa'ka'on salitong, paqo' ocia'.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat papaya and drink tea.

bnn: madavoc ca sincoaz qodasnanaz salitong, macial ko'non.
english: The papaya grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

bnn: asa amin cak ocia' i qodasnanaz, macial amin qo'dan.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

bnn: mato tongqovali ka, moskon cak qodasno'az pit'ia petotongqovali.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

bnn: mahanat ta qodasno'az mahancom to petotongqovali, heza iskan, tolkok, bahat, hezang qazoqazo'.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

bnn: mina'onin tongqovali, monhan cam pisanglavan matingoc sanglav.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

bnn: siza' a qodasno'az madia hotan, tai cin tilkom, napa'adas zako molomaq.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

bnn: namodanin cak, topaon zako nai to namoqnang cak mon'iti sado mo'o.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

bnn: adason cam haip sinsi' monhan sado'an tesmomot, tidelaz cam han hilav mabaliv kipo'.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

bnn: mokonbo'in topaka sinsi' to "maqa han tanangaos aiza ka loqe, maqa han tanhiko' aiza ka ivot, anaka sado.
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

bnn: mapising cak ivot, pangqa ni cak sado ivot.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

bnn: sado cak madia loqe', ihan nai daza' lokic kosbabai, osado'an cak toqo ihan konbo toszoq lokic masabaq.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

bnn: maqa kombo di ka heza zo, oma' cin koknav, niang cak qabas senido naidi, manaskal cak haip mon'iti sado.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

bnn: madia nak ka sinlasasing na pasado zako tamatina.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

bnn: maqe moqnin na taskon cak tamatina nak mon'iti.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

bnn: maqe pal'on haipi, dosa' cak toqas nak monhan Taito' tantongo han pantama'on nam.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

bnn: minihan cam Mihavaz tondaza' kisia' monhan Taito'.
english: We took the train from Shuili to Taitung.

bnn: kahanin cam Taito', ma'onting nga pantama'on lehleh monhan pando'anlehleh anpasdo zami.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

bnn: maqa pando'anlehleh ka nito daqvisan ni lomaq pantama'on, mahiv ma'onting lehleh ka ka'ita'in.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

bnn: heza madaing sepokan sinepok han ngalan lomaq pantama'on, tincozinsa' cam mon'ita.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

bnn: han sepokan sinepok, dason cam pantama'on nam paka'on sidi tondaza' oma'.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

bnn: sanavan'in, moskon cam monhan maci' ma'on.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

bnn: madia lehleh han maci', pangqa tondaza' cam otovai' mon'ita'.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

bnn: mato namodanin na, oka a otovai' tangqai'io'on bonon, moazin cam tonbaso' modan.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

bnn: hanin cam lopako Nanto', nito qanciap to kino'ananin opa ka otovai' i pantama'on.
english: Now that we are back in Nantu, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

bnn: ihan nam tamazo'an na lomaq to ova'azng, panto'in na molosqo' cam monhan Taicio', civong ihan baq miqomic.
english: When we were young, our family lived in tamazu'an. After I started school, we moved to Taichung and have been living in the city ever since.

bnn: monhanin panto'daing, masipol cak pali'onin iniqomican takisilazan, to'ipin cak maqanciap icia takitaivang di vevivevi sidoq to iniqomican.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

bnn: pangqa, mato pal'o'on haip qamisan, dosa cak ki masitoqas nak monhan acang macingav madadengaz, na'asa maqanciap anak'anak sidoq to iniqomican.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

bnn: mavo'onin qamisan na qodas, qala talmintokang sado'an.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

bnn: cingavan zami to ma'aq qa qancepon cia qalinga, malmanano' naip malasbonon, maqanciap amin malastolo cin malaspot hezang malaslepon.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Bunun, as well as Chinese, Hokkien and Japanese.

bnn: cingavan zami naip todipin cam maqanciap, tikicang naip to pinanamin malaslepon, mato kokozakin na madia pasaqalan pot cin tolo, pangqa madia cia ka qancepon qalinga.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, and he knows many Hokkien and Chinese at work, so he can speak so many languages.

bnn: mato macingav cam ma, madia cia madadengaz za palcicia takiqabas qanop to snkokoza.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

bnn: qalto ni cam amin itqal, qala koci'an zami lingva lasasing, namaqto oqna'on manengkal tan'a.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

bnn: mato atikicang cam ma nito saqal anak'anak sidoq to iniqomican, miliskin anak'anak to bonon na maz'avdaingaz.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

bnn: malassaqalin na, miliskin anak'anak to bonnon na, totoza' to makisvevi, heza'an kainaskalan.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Bunun is unique and something to be proud of.

bnn: namolomaq ti a masinoba' haip sanavan.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

bnn: dosa' cak ki qodasno'az monhan babalivan mabaliv tolkok, mahanat macial isqol ispaka'on masinoba' sanavanin.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

bnn: laqai' cam balivansanglav madia' a ma'o'ovol to sanglav.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

bnn: mabaliv cam ingsai', tanbongna' cin tolacdangqac.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

bnn: topa ka dinglan babalivan koko'on to, "madavoc nak ka bonglai' cin qalop, baliva tikic!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

bnn: laqai' cam babalivan titi', topa ka babalivan to, "maq so a balivon? madaing haip pa tolkok ka malac taosaba coi tas'a."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

bnn: maqlican na qodasno'az, macingav nip babalivan to, "maqto opa iasoi' tikic."
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

bnn: qala topa ka babalivan to, "iasoi'in 'ni'in maqto vanaqan."
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

bnn: topa ka dingalan babalivan to, "baliva iskan nak, manak ka iskan na madaing nga iasoi."
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

bnn: kinozin mabaliv cam tolkok mabaliv amin iskan, molomaq mahanat tas'a pangka isqol.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

bnn: kalingva' a masinoba to, "mocqa nito maqto pal'o'on, nahanin monin islongqo'an molomaq."
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

bnn: topa ka qodasno'az to, "madia'in na sinhanat, ona'oi ka bonon moskon ma'on!"
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

bnn: ona'on zami ka tec'an cin kaviaz, moskon ma'on madia isqol to sanavan.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

bnn: heza nak oskonan topa'on to Kimat, qanglac naip minpongol madas qemangsot.
english: I have a classmate named Kimat, he often forgets to bring things.

bnn: maca isnava'anin na, simol naip han oskonan inpico', isqeqesqes minton patasan to haqel.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

bnn: mato mioc'an, moposan, moti'on, pasimolanng zami naip qemangsot.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

bnn: qala madikla' nip pi, qanglac simol la nito macoqes qemangsot.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

bnn: dongzavin amin cam nito asa pasimol cai qemangsot.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

bnn: heza to tas'a qani'an moskon cam monata paqaqenan.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

bnn: mato han dan na, asa ka Kimat monata, qala minpongol naip madas haqel isqesqes.
english: On the way, Kimat wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

bnn: simol naip han oskonan haqel isqesqes, amin cam antalam topa to, oka amin nak inadas.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

bnn: tangicin na Kimat, mahao' naip topa to "makoa amo tona amin nito pasimol zako haqel isqesqes!"
english: Kimat burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

bnn: topaon oskonan to "opa ni aso anak madas, mosoto maca pasimol so'o qemangsot, ni aso qanciap macoqes!"
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

bnn: monkako'in laqbing, matingmot ta Kimat kahan kako', aminon Kimat ta sinimol cia qemangsot macoqes han oskonan.
english: The next day at school, Kimat arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

bnn: masihan na Kimat oskonan masomsom, topa to na'anakanakin naip madas qemangsot, miqomican oskonan pasimol cia qabas qemangsot.
english: Kimat apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.
My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

bnn: mato atikicang cak ka, dosa' nai tama ki pantama'on sanavan monata', madas nai via' cin bocol.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

bnn: maqe tosqangin na, mama' nai pinanaq tesmomot.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

bnn: minton cia vanis, minton cia haval, doandoan amin heza linas.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

bnn: mato soqesin mo'acang nano pavazonin nai ka bahi' nai, na'ispaqosil li tec'an.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

bnn: qelic cak topa ki tama to "namalavi cak qanop."
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

bnn: topa ka tama to todipi taldaingin aso kana adasonin aso."
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

bnn: maqanciap amin na bananaz han acang mahaqo' madamo tesmomot, maqanciap amin matas'i haqomocqot cin malqato'.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

bnn: maqanciap pa tama nak matas'i haqobantac, topa ka tama to "ishaqo' epi linas, asa ata to saqal dapan ni tesmomot, pihanon dan ni tesmomot ta haqo'."
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

bnn: tis'oni asa mahiav malavi madadengaz qanop, locbot cak pinanam malhaqo', nito talmadia' tishaqo'an na haqo' nak tesmomot.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

bnn: sado'an tama ka topaon cak cia to "namin'oni aso mamangan to qaqanop."
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

bnn: taldaingin cak lopako, angqeli'an cak bocolkahkah cin kos, malavi ki tama moskon qanop.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

bnn: mocoqesin na onna qenanop tesmomot ispaqosil tec'an.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

bnn: topa ka tama to "asa ata to matomacqeng memadadengaz to sintoqomic, maqto ata madia' bahi'."
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.

bnn: pito' cak toki' haip kahan kako'.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

bnn: kitnga'in, minsomin na sinsi', topa ka lavivi'an to "mindangkaza! masomsom!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

bnn: kinga'in isnava'an, isnava'an cam sinsi' malasbonon masipol sipolon.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Bunun language of numbers.

bnn: sisili cam sinsi' masipol, tosaoc cam sipolon to sintosaoc.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.
I have learned many Bunun languages.

bnn: daqdaqqanin cak monkako', daqdaqqanin cak pinanam malasbonon, patan'a zako tina nak.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Bunun language every day, and I want to tell my mother.
I was late for school this morning.

bnn: minpongol cak madas kavang, monhan kako'.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

bnn: moskon cak oskonan sado, hong to isnava'an.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

bnn: mato siking nga, simol cak han oskonan inpico' cin isqeqesqes.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

bnn: topa'on cak sinsi' to, "matingmot minoqo, ka'in to moqnang halacan!"
english: The teacher told me, Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!""

bnn: Tiang nga kaviaz nak, ova'az amin aipa Bonon.
english: My good friend's name is Tiang, and he is also an Bunun child.

bnn: moskon cam ihan Malavi' to acang masipol.
english: We study together in the Malavi' tribe.

bnn: locbot cam moskon tan'a madadengaz taqo paliqabasan, amin cam maqanciap malasBonon.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Bunun proficiently.

bnn: madaqvas cak ka masboq, maqa Tiang nga mapotis sa makois.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Tiang is short and thin.

bnn: makackac ca Tiang nga, amin cam asa cia.
english: Tiang is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

bnn: pintataiv haip pa kako', madia' 'a onpintataov.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

bnn: heza' pasibotbot, katondaq mali', tindangkol, olozi', manaq bocolkahkah.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

bnn: mato tindangkol cak ka, motingkol la, qedangon na qa'.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.
But I stood up and continued running forward.

bnn: mato ka'ita'in cak ka amin na bonon manaskal.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

bnn: qal to ni to lavai' 'a, manaskal cak, opa sokanaqtong cak pintataiv.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

bnn: dosa' cak tama takna tantongo han tamaSai'.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

bnn: taqo'an cam cia to, "motoszoq qa tatavi ka."
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

bnn: mato matas'i naip tatavi ka, minihan daza' tatavi moqalqal.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

bnn: madas sa tama ki titi'qanvang cin pinong ispaska' 'i tamaSai'.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

bnn: dosa' cak ki tamaSai' ihan palan pababazbaz, madia' cia ka sintaqo paliqabasan.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

bnn: mato namodanin cak ka, topa ka tamaSai' to taldaqvasin cak ka mintalmindokin."
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

bnn: topa cak to, "maca mincialin na bantac ci tamaSai' 'a, tantongo han lomaq nam."
english: I said, When your foot gets better

bnn: ihan 2022 qamisan, palaqanciap pa Seho' to maqa takisilaza to niovonsio' 'a maqto kopa'on nganBonon mapatas.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

bnn: macingav cak ki malbonto topa ki Seho' to, "kopa'on nganBonon mapatas" han niovonsio', talmindo to Tiang tasikavan.
english: I interviewed Tiang tasikavan, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

bnn: patopakin cak cia to namaca pal'o'on namonhan cak lomaq cia macingav.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

bnn: mato ihan pacingav va, taqo'an cak cia to mini'icaqa ngan cia, adason cak cia pasaqal li tastolomaq cia cin acang cia.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

bnn: cingavan zako naip to makoa cona asa'on na ngan mahovaiv, niqa macial la sinpatas qabas?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

bnn: topa naip zako to, "opa maqa malastolo ka ni to maqto topa ki anakanak to ngan tolivaon ni bonon loklac to Ti sinsi' isqaqenanin aipi.
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him \Di Xian Sheng

bnn: topa ka Tiang tasikavan to, "maqa mamanto to ngan na cia koci'an malasBonon mapatas, maqa ngan na pasqal li sidoq cin tastolomaq, maqto'ang nga Bonon mocoqes kilim mi ngan mapatas."
english: Tiang tasikavan said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

bnn: malavi cak takna qodasno'az mohan onapokan babalivan, madas sa qodasno'az madia' sincoaz cia sanglav, matas'i amin itocia Bonon to kokonon iscav bonon.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

bnn: amin na bonon asa ki babalivan ni qodasno'az, madia' bonon mabaliv daqpot cin daqpotpa'ic, madia' bonon minsoma tanam ma'on sinhanat cia sanglav.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

bnn: macial konon na sinhanat cia li'li' cin qesing dolaz, hezang vanis hibolan maqav sinhanat to titi', madia' bonon hancoman, masan tidelaz han babalivan nam.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

bnn: mahanat ta qodasno'az zi kokonon na, ihan cak ngalan loloklac ci bonon, pidengon zako loklac to, "anak'anak ka sanglav sincoaz, ni to cinolan io' tel'anak tal'ia to sanglav, kava mohan di mabaliv!"
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

bnn: mahiav nam ma isbabaliv aminon mabaliv, topa ka qodasno'az to, "opa heza' aso kadangaz za."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

bnn: minihan sinkokoza di, oqancepan cak itocia bonon ismot cin kokonon to qanciap, moso to oqancepan ni icia babalivan to ineqdi'an.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

bnn: sado ki qodasno'an malkacia itobonon kokonon to qanciap, mastan cak matomaceqeng onaskalan.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.

bnn: Iha'an azak pito' tatnolan monha'an sipolan.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

bnn: Masipolin, mokombo'in tataqo'an ca tataqo, topa ca pancang to "mindoldola, masomsoma."
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

bnn: Matacqait ata bazbaz topa to "miqomicang tataqo."
Uoto masipol todiip, taqo'an azam tataqo malasbonon masipol is paitasanpia.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the Bunun language of numbers.

bnn: Malavi azam is tataqo silisili bazbaz, tosasaoc azam is paitasanpia.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.

bnn: Madia' sala ca pisqancaiponin zako malasbonon a qalinga.
english: I have learned many Bunun languages.

bnn: Daqdaqanin azak monsipolan, daqdaqanin azak pisqanciap malasbonon, na isbazbazko patan'a tina.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the Bunun language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

bnn: Abis ca ngaan it tama naak.
Ival ca nggan it tina naak.
Maiza tatini toqasnanaz naak, topa'on to Bato, mac'an qan ta'a ca qamisan cia haip.
english: I have a brother, his name is Batu, he is 11 years old.
We study in the same school.

bnn: Asa azak it toqasnanaz naak tosasaoc.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

bnn: Asa azak tonhapav, maca mol'oon, na moskon azam tatlomaq tonhapav.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

bnn: Asa azak papacqal' is kaviaz, na maqto' azam moskon tosasaoc ciin tonhapav.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.
There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

bnn: Aloskonan azak tama, tina, toqasnanaz ciin toqasnao'az.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.

bnn: Malaongkav hala ca tama naak, sasaipok ca tama naak.
english: My father is tall and he is a policeman.

bnn: Makios ca tina naak, ising ca tina naak.
english: My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

bnn: Malasbonon ca tama pababazbaz zamon ca ilomaq.
english: My father speaks the ethnic language with us at home.

bnn: Maca mol'oon tanabal a mo'amin azam mon'acang.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

bnn: Moskon azak it toqas naak madamos cicioq.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.

bnn: Mantan azak asa salas tatlomaq naam.
english: I like our family very much.

bnn: Moskon azak tina monata' kavivila' haip.
english: I went out with my mother today.

bnn: Masanglav sala ca diqanin, nii' to maci'it, nii' amin macaklo ca diqanin, makazhav sala ca hivhiv.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

bnn: Mal'anogqo' azam is moot ma'os pang, savali'an azam is vali, maklang sala tan'aon.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.

bnn: Mina'onin to qani'an, mindangqac ca diqanin.
english: In the afternoon, the sky turned red.

bnn: Macingav azak tina to, makoa ca diqanin cona mindangqac.
english: I asked my mother why the sky is red.

bnn: Topa ca tina to, qaal na maiza ca lovlov.
english: Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

bnn: Uka' is lohom to sananvan, mintasal ca bintoqan.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

bnn: Kamicqang is daan to na molomaq, masisaopa bintoqan ca is'ang min'asaz.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars

bnn: Ka'ang qa ca lovlov mindadoo maipa ti', asang azak monata' kavivila'.
english: I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

bnn: Ingalan is lomaq naam ca sipolan, daqdaqanin azak tan'anak monsipolan, tan'anak amin molomaq.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

bnn: Nii' to madaing ca sipolan naak, nii' to madia' ca masisipol, mo'amin papanqal.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

bnn: Mo'amin ca masisipol mo'inon ha'an vangko, moskon pakamali', moskon pababazbaz.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

bnn: Moskon amin zamon ca tataqo kavivila', maitatlomaq ca sipolani'.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

bnn: Daqdaqanin azam ma'asik, mo'amin siningzav is taqoqo'anin maqaisvaz.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

bnn: Maiza ca maqaisqais is taongkol, maiza ca ma'asik.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

bnn: Ma'asik azam amin ciki'ciki' is sipolan, aminon paqosil pakadangaz ca kokozaon, daqdaqanin maningzav sala ca sipolan.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

bnn: Mon'acang azak tantongo ha'an qodasnanaz takna.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

bnn: Talbonton azam nii' to pasadoo, mantan azak min'asaz cia.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

bnn: Sadoon zakon at qodas a, mosoo' paka'on zakon sikoa, paqoo' zakon savil.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

bnn: Mantan madavoc ca sikoa sincoaz it qodasnanaz, mantan macial kaonon.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

bnn: Mazima azak savil it qodasnanaz, macial amin qoo'an.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

bnn: Uoto tostosvalin, mosko azak it qodasnao'az pitdia paito qani'an.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

bnn: Malcikaopata' ca sinhanat it qodasnao'az a paito qani'an, maiza ca kaan, tolkok, bahat, maiza amin ca qazoqazo'.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

bnn: Mina'onin is paito qani'an a, monha'an azam pinsanglavan matingoc is sanglav.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

bnn: Madia' sala ca siniza' it qodasnao'az a hotan, taii' ciin calo iscaiv zakon, na ispa'adas zakon molomaq.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

bnn: Pasomsom azak nai to modaan, taqo to na moqna'ang tantongo nai'an ca ickoin.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

bnn: Adason azam tataqo monha'an patismomootan haip diqanin, iha'an azam okombo'an masindailaz mabaliv is kipo'.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

bnn: Mokombo'in azam is patismomootan a, topa ca tataqo to "loqai' ca ha'an tantangaos, ivot ca ha'an hiko', ananaka sadoo."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

bnn: Mapising azak is ivot, daqat nii' azak sadoos ivotivot.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

bnn: Madia' sala ca loqai' sado'anko, idaza' a nais lokic kosbabai, sadoo azak amin tocqo' ikombo' is hoqtong masabaq.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

bnn: Maiza ca coo', tancikis, ciin hoqnavdaing iha'an patismomootan, mii'ang azak qabas sinadoos tismomoot mangki', sinadoon azak haip a manahip sala ca is'ang.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.

bnn: Madia' sala ca siniza' inaak a qaningo, iscaiv it tamatina pasadoo nai.
english: I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

bnn: Na moskon azak it tamatina maipa ti' maca moqnin.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

bnn: Iha'an inol'oan dii, moskon azak it toqasnao'az montaito' ha'an pantamaon naak tantongo.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

bnn: Minaha'an azam Taihoko' tonlaihlihsapoz panha'an Taito'.
english: We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

bnn: Kaca'anin Taito' a, ma'onting laihlih ca pantamaon naak monha'an ol'oanlaihlih anpasdoo zamon.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

bnn: Nii' to daqvisan is ol'oanlaihlih ca lomaq it pantamaon naak, podaan tokoc is laihlih a kaca'anin ta'.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

bnn: Maiza ca madaing sala ka sasaipokas sinaipok ingalan lomaq it pantamaon naak, moskon azam tonpaqais monha'an sasaipokan.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

bnn: Uoto ha'an sasaipokan, adason azam pantamaon naak paka'on sidi ciin tancikis.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

bnn: Sanavanin, moskon azam monmicqang'acang ma'on qaisang.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

bnn: Madia' sala ca laihlih ha'an micqang'acang, daqat tonpaopoh azam maipata'.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

bnn: Na modaanin azam a, malolon to monghav tanqa'io'os bonon ca paopoh, daqat mo'hazin azam tonlaihlihqaongo' mocoqais.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

bnn: Kaha'anin azam Taihoko' haip, niapang ti inko'ananin naopa ca paopoh kit pantamaon naak.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

bnn: Iha'an Qoqoaz ca lomaq naam to takiocang, masipolin a molosqo monha'an Qabinaz, oa' takaha'anin bokzav miqomic.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Qabinaz. After I started school, we moved to Puli and have been living in the city ever since.

bnn: Masipolin is sipolandaing, masipolak is ito iniqomicas Bononcoko' a sipolon, minqanciap to maca Bononcoko' ha'an Taivang ti' a madia' sala ca vaivivaivi ka iniqomican.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

bnn: Daqat, iha'an haip qamisan to tanabal dii, moskon azak it toqasnanaz mon'acang macicingav is madadaingaz, asat maqanciap is inak'anak a iniqomican.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

bnn: Ponmavaao'onin qamisan ca madaingaz dii, ooto maopang is talnaqtongin a bonon sadoo'an.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

bnn: Pacingvan zako ka cia to ma'az ca qalinga qancaipon bazbaz, mantan a cia maqancia bazbaz is malasqai'ial, maqanciap amin bazbaz is malastaoloo ciin malaspoot.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Japanese, as well as Atayal, Hokkien and Chinese.

bnn: Macingavak cia ha maqanciapin to, taoloo ca binanao'az cia, madia' sala ca poot pacqalan ha'an kokoza'an cia, daqat madia' ca qalingaz qancaipon cia bazbaz.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Chinese, and he knows many Hokkien at work, so he can speak so many languages.

bnn: Uoto pacingavan zami todiip a, palaqanciap ca madaingaz diis madia' sala ka ito qabas palaciat qanop a taiklac.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

bnn: Altopat nii' to aminon macqal to tokokoa ca sinbabazbaz, Uoto koci'aon zami tingvatikic pinqaningo, na maqto'ang sicqason tan'a.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

bnn: Uoto takiocang azak nii'ang macqal is inak'anak a iniqomican, maz'av tokoc dii bononcoko' ca sidoq inaak amin.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

bnn: Todiipin to minmadia'in ca sinpacqalan, mina'is'ang maqanciap to maca inakan inaak Bononi' a mantan makanvaivi, maqto'ang iskokoniv.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Bunun is unique and something to be proud of.

bnn: Haip qani'an to na minsanavan, na molomaqin ca naoba'nanaz.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

bnn: Moskon azak it qodasnao'az monca'an icivaa' mabaliv is tolkok, palasanoc is mantan macial a paito sanavan na ispaka'on naoba'nanaz.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

bnn: Laqai' azam is babalivansanglav a, madia' sala ca macicial a sanglav ha'an balivansanglav.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

bnn: Mabaliv azam is sanglavkaboo', tankaono ciin tao'lacdangqac.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

bnn: Maca ingalan taimicia babalivas kokotdaqon topa' to, "mantan madavoc ca onglai ciin qalop inaak, mabaliva tokoc!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

bnn: Mabaliv azam is onglai ciin qalop.
Laqai' azam babalivas qaso', topa ca taimicia to, "ma'az ca balivon so'o? masqa' masimal amin ca tolkok haip, taao saba coii ca ta'a."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

bnn: Tan'aon qodasnao'az to mantan maqlic sala, oa' macingav is taimicia to maqto'ang naopa vanaqan tokoc.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

bnn: Uoto topa ca taimicia to naot nii'in dangpia ta' coii, nii'in maqto' vanaqan.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

bnn: Bazbaz ca ingalan a taimicia to, noqan mabaliv is kaan inaak i', mamasqa' ca kaan naak nii' amin to maqlic.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

bnn: Mabalivin azam is tolkok ciin kaan to hiko'in, molomaq mahanat is tatpangka' a qoqool.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.

bnn: Malabonto matatala ha, mindomdomin ca diqanin.
english: After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

bnn: Katingva' ca naoba'nanaz molomaq taqo to, minkava' nii' to maqto'pol'oon ca malalasti', maca ha'anin moqnin inol'oan na molomaqin.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

bnn: Topa kat qodasnao'az to na palcikaopata'in is sinpitdia ki' a, amini loklac ca mangka' na moskon ma'on!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

bnn: Loklac azam is kitlomaq, kaviaz, oskonan ma'os mantan macial sala kao'on a paito sanavan.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

bnn: Maiza tatini ka tokozako, malabonto ka cia minpongol is mama'az.
english: I have a classmate named Qanciaz, he often forgets to bring things.

bnn: Todiip maca masipol, simol a cia ispapatas, isqaqaisqais cina papatasan ha'an tokocia.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

bnn: Maca moc'anang, moposan, moti'on a, na pasilolanang is doma' a cia mama'az.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

bnn: Uoto, maiza ca madikla'a talmaopa'an cia, malabonto sisimol is mama'az a nii' to macoqais.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

bnn: Ihiko'in a nii'in ca doma' asa pasimol cia mama'az.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

bnn: Maiza tatdiqanin, moskon azam modadaan kavivila'.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

bnn: Panmicqang is daan a, si'a'aoma kat Qanciaz, ooto minpongol a cia madas is haqailqaisqais.
english: On the way, Qanciaz wanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

bnn: Makos'aiv a cia haqailqaisqais ha'an tokocia, ooto mo'amin ca doma' antalam topa to, nii' azam amin madas.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

bnn: Tangic at Qanciaz dii nii'in maqanciap to na masikoa. Mahao' a cia topa to, makoa amoo cona mo'amin nii' to pasimol zakon is haqailqaisqais!
english: Qanciaz burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

bnn: Taqo'an tokocia kat cia to, nii' asoo anak'anak andas'andas, maopa amin to, na ispasimol so'on ca mama'az a, nii' aso longolongo macoqais!
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

bnn: Moqnin masipol to lakbingin, kantingmot sala kat Qanciaz monsipolan, aminon Qanciaz ca sinimol cia ka mama'az macoqais iscaiv is tokocia.
english: The next day at school, Qanciaz arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

bnn: Somsomon Qanciaz ca tokocia, topa amin to na anak'anakin a cia madas is mama'az, masomsom amin is tokocia dii mina'is'ang pasimol cias mama'az to tangaosang.
english: Qanciaz apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.

bnn: Nomo' malkaqanop at tama naak ha'an acang.
english: My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

bnn: Uoto ova'azang azak, na sanavan at tama ciin pantamaon monata', madas is viia' ciin bocol.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

bnn: Uoca mincingqalin ca diqanin, na madas a nai pinanaq a mama'az mocoqais.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

bnn: Mintong ciat vanis, mintong ciat haval, na minton maiza amin ca linas.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.

bnn: Iha'an a nai acang picial pavaz is sinpapanak, sisolavis doma' a bonon.
english: They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

bnn: Malabonto azak pinqalisoal it tama, na asat malavi tama tinqanop.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

bnn: Topa kat tama to, maca taldaingin azak ka na dason cia azak moskon maipata'.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

bnn: Maqanciap amin makohaqo madamos tismomoot ca taka'acang a bananaz, maqanciap a nai matas'is haqodoon ciin malaqato'.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

bnn: Mantan at tama naak maqanciap matas'is haqodoon, topa kat tama to, isdamos linas ca dii, asat macqas sadoo dapan is mama'az, na picanon daan laqaibas mama'azi' ca haqo.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

bnn: Tis'onin na mahiav moskon is madadaingaz tinqanop, daqdaqanin azak pisqanciap mahaqo, toza' to maqto' madamos mama'az ca haqo naak.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

bnn: Sadoo'an tama naak a topa zakon to, na zako dao qabasin ca mantan matamasaz a malaqanop to bonon.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

bnn: Taldaingin azak haip, ama'on zako ca inaak a bocolkaka ciin koos, malavit tama moskon tinqanop.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.

bnn: Mato mocoqaisin a nai mon'acang a isolavis doma' taka'acang bonon ca sinpapanaq a mama'az.
english: When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

bnn: Topa kat tama to, asat masomsomtas maitangosin a madadaingaz macaiv is bahi', maqto'ang pasiza'on iton ca malcikaopa ta' a mama'az.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.

bnn: Sihalacan azak monha'an sipolan to tingmot.
english: I was late for school this morning.

bnn: Minpongol azak madas kavang to, monha'an sipolan.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

bnn: Moskon azak tokozako sadoo haqailsipolon to, masipol.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

bnn: Pasimolan azak tokozako ispapatas ciin isqaqaisqais to, patanam.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

bnn: Bazbaz zakon ca tataqo to, "tingmota mindangkaz ca moqnin, ka'in to sihalacan!"
english: The teacher told me, Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!""

bnn: Kaviaz daingaz inaak topa'on to Tanpilic, Uva'az amin a cias Bonon.
english: My good friend's name is Tanpilic, and he is also an Bunun child.
We study together in the Ququaz tribe.

bnn: Malocbot azam moskon tan'as madadaingaz bazbaz is qaiqabasan to qalinga, mo'amin azam maqanciap malasbonon.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the Bunun proficiently.

bnn: Malaongkav azak a masmoq amin, mapotis at Tanpilic a makois amin.
english: I am tall and overweight, while Tanpilic is short and thin.

bnn: Mina'ia'ang sala kat Tanpilic ca mankama'az, asaon salas doma' a miniqomic.
english: Tanpilic is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

bnn: Kavivila' palontan ca sipolan haip diqanin, madia' sala ca sinkanal is sipolan a palontanon.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

bnn: Maiza ca pasibotbot, katondaqmali', malilia, iongi' ciin manaq bocolkaka.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

bnn: Laplaq azak to malilia todiip, milo'lo' ca qaa', madia' sala ca tiqoc.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.
But I stood up and continued running forward.

bnn: Pandiipin azak a mo'amin ca bonon manahip sala.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

bnn: Qalto nii' to lavai', ooto mantan azak manahip sala, maopa'i saonaqtongan zako ca palontan dii.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

bnn: Moskon azak tama tantongo ha'an pantamaon naak takna.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

bnn: Milo'lo' ca bantac it pantamaon naak.
Taqo'an cia azam to motoszoq ca tatavis lomaq.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

bnn: Minaca'an a cia tatavi moqalqal to sikangna ka cias tatavi.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

bnn: Madas at tamas qaso'qanvang ciin saviki' iscaiv it pantamaon naak.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

bnn: Moskon azak it pantamaon naak iha'an sabaqan pababazbaz, taqo ka cia madia' sala ka qaiqabasan to qalinga.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

bnn: Tantangaos is na modaanak, matomacqaing zakon at pantamaon to taldaingin, mintalmindoo amin.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

bnn: Topa azak to, "Tamanama', mol'oang maca mincialin ca bantac, na monca'an amin lomaq naam kavivila' ca ickoinin."
english: I said, When your foot gets better

bnn: Iha'an 2022 qamisan, mon'anpok ca sasbinaz palaqanciap is ito Bononcoko'i' a cibonsio' to maqto' hazon palasbononon papatas is ngaan.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

bnn: Maicingavak is mintalmindoo ka bonon inita acang Nasing Balincinan, ponpipiin pondaza' is paitasan na asa dao hazon palasbononon papatas ca ngaan ha'an cibonsio'.
english: I interviewed Nasing Balincinan, a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

bnn: Patataqon azak icia to na monha'an lomaq cia tantongo maca ha'an inol'oan dii.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

bnn: Ha'an sinpacingav dii ha, papacqal zakon a cia to mina'ica ca ngaan icia dii, madas amin zakon papacqal is kitlomaq icia, acang icia.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

bnn: Pacingavon zako to mazang siqocal toza' pahovaiv is ngaan, nii' to macial ca maopa qabas a' papatas?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

bnn: Topa kat Nasing to, "ciat malasbonon papatas is ngaan ca nano' ngaan inita', maca ngaan inita' i' a nano' sinpasnava' is sidoq nita', kitlomaq inita', ainakan nita' ti cima, min'asaz to katnoang minmadia' ca Bononi' mocoqais kilim is inak'anak a ngaan."
english: Nasing said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

bnn: Moskonak qodasnao'az takna monca'an po'inonas isbabaliv malkaciat langqa'babalivan, madas at qodasnao'az is inak'anak cia sincoaz a sanglavsanglav, matas'i ka cia amin is ito Bononcoko' kakaonon na balivos miniqomic.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

bnn: Asaon salas bonon ca langqa'babalivan it qodasnao'az, madia' sala ca bonon mabaliv is daqpoot ciin pa'ic, madia' sala ca bonon tanam ma'os sinhanat icia ka qoqool.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

bnn: Mantan macial sala kaonon ca sinhanat icia ka li'li' ciin dolazqaising, maiza amin ca koci'aon maqav sinpisomal a qaso'vanis, madia' sala ca bonon kaidaas tahon cia, mo'amin ca bonon monha'an langqa'babalivan icia masinlaoto.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

bnn: Uoca mahanat ca qodasnao'az is mama'az a, na ingalanak malkaciat taitongo, ingalanak sidaing is qalinga loklac to, "mo'amin inak'anak sincoaz ca sanglavsanglav, nii' to ponda'as ioo', haiva maipa dii mabaliv."
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

bnn: Mahiav sala ca mama'az naam aminon isbaliv, topa ka qodasnao'az to, "ala nii'ang it maizakas ha'an ti' kadangazi'."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

bnn: Maca sinkokoza dii ha, oqancaipanak is ito Bononcoko' a taiklac is motmoot ciin kakaonon, tan'a amin sinango'an is malkaciat langqa'babalivan mangki'.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

bnn: Sadoo qodasnao'az to mantan asa salas nano' talmaopa'an a kakaonon, kanaha'an azak is is'ang tan'a to mantan ac kini' kakonivon ciin kabahi'on sala.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.
